36
00:03:33,130 --> 00:03:34,715
[slave grunting]

37
00:03:55,377 --> 00:03:56,461
Whoa.

38
00:04:03,991 --> 00:04:04,995
Whoa.

39
00:04:19,801 --> 00:04:22,554
Who's that stumbling around in the dark?

40
00:04:23,488 --> 00:04:26,600
State your business,
or prepare to get winged.

41
00:04:27,684 --> 00:04:31,229
Calm yourselves, gentlemen.
I mean you no harm.

42
00:04:32,564 --> 00:04:35,275
I'm simply a fellow weary traveler.

43
00:04:35,358 --> 00:04:36,443
Whoa!

44
00:04:38,737 --> 00:04:40,489
Good, cold evening, gentlemen.

45
00:04:40,572 --> 00:04:44,785
I'm looking for a pair of slave traders
that go by the name of the Speck Brothers.

46
00:04:44,910 --> 00:04:45,994
Might that be you?

47
00:04:47,996 --> 00:04:50,248
-[Ace] Who wants to know?
-Well, I do.

48
00:04:50,832 --> 00:04:53,126
I'm Dr. King Schultz.
This is my horse, Fritz.

49
00:04:54,544 --> 00:04:57,506
-What kind of doctor?
-[Schultz] Dentist.

50
00:04:58,173 --> 00:04:59,466
Now, are you the Speck Brothers,

51
00:04:59,591 --> 00:05:02,469
and did you purchase those men
at the Greenville slave auction?

52
00:05:02,594 --> 00:05:05,347
-So what?
-So, I wish to parley with you.

53
00:05:05,428 --> 00:05:06,328
Speak English.

54
00:05:06,515 --> 00:05:08,225
[chuckling] I'm sorry.

55
00:05:08,934 --> 00:05:11,061
Please forgive me.
It is a second language.

56
00:05:11,144 --> 00:05:14,648
Now, amongst your inventory,
I've been led to believe,

57
00:05:14,731 --> 00:05:16,900
is a specimen I'm keen to acquire.

58
00:05:17,275 --> 00:05:18,777
Hello, you poor devils.

59
00:05:20,111 --> 00:05:25,408
Is there one amongst you who was formerly
a resident of the Carrucan plantation?

60
00:05:26,952 --> 00:05:28,578
[Django] I'm from the Carrucan plantation.

61
00:05:30,872 --> 00:05:31,960
Who said that?

62
00:06:19,296 --> 00:06:20,297
What's your name?

63
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:25,975
Django.

64
00:06:27,178 --> 00:06:29,222
Then you are exactly
the one I'm looking for.

65
00:06:31,474 --> 00:06:33,226
Do you know who the Brittle brothers are?

66
00:06:37,376 --> 00:06:38,398
Who are they?

67
00:06:40,901 --> 00:06:41,981
Big John.

68
00:06:43,111 --> 00:06:44,165
Ellis.

69
00:06:45,697 --> 00:06:46,781
Roger.

70
00:06:47,198 --> 00:06:49,284
Sometime they call him Little Raj.

71
00:06:51,202 --> 00:06:53,246
They was overseers
at the Carrucan plantation.

72
00:06:53,622 --> 00:06:54,623
Not anymore.

73
00:06:58,001 --> 00:07:02,297
Tell me, if you were to see any
of these three gentlemen again,

74
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:04,090
-would you recognize them?
-[Ace] Hey.

75
00:07:05,342 --> 00:07:07,761
-Stop talking to him like that.
-Like what?

76
00:07:08,178 --> 00:07:09,212
Like that.

77
00:07:09,471 --> 00:07:11,973
My good man,
I'm simply trying to ascertain--

78
00:07:12,057 --> 00:07:13,475
Speak English, goddamn it.

79
00:07:14,225 --> 00:07:20,315
Everybody calm down. I'm simply a customer
trying to conduct a transaction.

80
00:07:20,398 --> 00:07:22,984
I don't care. No sale. Now, off with you.

81
00:07:23,193 --> 00:07:26,154
Don't be ridiculous.
Of course they're for sale.

82
00:07:27,197 --> 00:07:28,208
[Ace] Move it.

83
00:07:28,907 --> 00:07:33,745
My good man, did you simply get
carried away with your dramatic gesture,

84
00:07:33,828 --> 00:07:36,998
or are you pointing your weapon at me
with lethal intention?

85
00:07:37,207 --> 00:07:38,260
[cocks gun]

86
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,377
Last chance, fancy pants.

87
00:07:41,920 --> 00:07:43,546
Oh, very well.

88
00:07:47,550 --> 00:07:49,803
[Dicky screaming]

89
00:08:00,939 --> 00:08:01,982
[Dicky groaning]

90
00:08:08,405 --> 00:08:11,992
[Dicky screaming]

91
00:08:13,201 --> 00:08:17,747
I'm sorry to put a bullet in your beast,
but I didn't want you to do anything rash

92
00:08:17,831 --> 00:08:20,041
before you had a moment
to come to your senses.

93
00:08:20,291 --> 00:08:23,420
You goddamn son of a bitch!

94
00:08:23,962 --> 00:08:25,964
-You shot Roscoe!
-[Schultz] Well...

95
00:08:26,840 --> 00:08:28,133
[Dicky] And you killed Ace!

96
00:08:28,508 --> 00:08:31,386
I only shot your brother
once he threatened to shoot me.

97
00:08:31,553 --> 00:08:34,472
And I do believe I have...
One, two, three, four...

98
00:08:34,556 --> 00:08:37,517
Five witnesses who can
attest to that fact.

99
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:40,478
-Damn leg's busted.
-No doubt.

100
00:08:40,562 --> 00:08:43,398
Now, if you could keep your caterwauling
down to a minimum,

101
00:08:43,481 --> 00:08:46,401
I'd like to finish my line of inquiry
with young Django.

102
00:08:46,818 --> 00:08:50,030
[Dicky screaming]

103
00:08:50,822 --> 00:08:53,450
-[Dicky] God-fucking-damn it!
-As I was saying...

104
00:08:54,409 --> 00:08:56,578
if you were to see
the Brittle brothers again,

105
00:08:56,828 --> 00:08:58,079
you could recognize them?

106
00:08:58,705 --> 00:08:59,721
Yeah.

107
00:09:00,623 --> 00:09:03,043
Sold American! So, Mr. Speck?

108
00:09:03,334 --> 00:09:05,545
Mr. Speck, how much
for young Django, here?

109
00:09:11,384 --> 00:09:13,470
That iron is nasty business.

110
00:09:19,392 --> 00:09:20,852
Could you hold this for a moment?

111
00:09:23,075 --> 00:09:24,147
Thank you.

112
00:09:24,481 --> 00:09:26,441
Django, get up on that horse.

113
00:09:27,358 --> 00:09:28,818
Also, if I were you,

114
00:09:29,110 --> 00:09:32,781
I'd take that winter coat
the dear, departed Speck left behind.

115
00:09:47,253 --> 00:09:50,423
Nigger! Don't you touch my brother's coat.

116
00:09:59,933 --> 00:10:02,393
[screams]

117
00:10:02,477 --> 00:10:04,062
[Dicky] Goddamn it!

118
00:10:04,896 --> 00:10:06,564
[Dicky groans]

119
00:10:08,858 --> 00:10:13,279
One hundred, ten, twenty,

120
00:10:14,030 --> 00:10:15,365
and five...

121
00:10:17,117 --> 00:10:20,411
for young Django, here. And since
he won't be needing it anymore,

122
00:10:20,495 --> 00:10:22,789
I'd like to purchase your brother's nag.

123
00:10:23,623 --> 00:10:25,792
Also, Mr. Speck,

124
00:10:26,042 --> 00:10:29,379
I'm afraid I will require a bill of sale.
Do you have one?

125
00:10:30,969 --> 00:10:32,841
You go to hell, dentist!

126
00:10:33,842 --> 00:10:35,009
I thought not.

127
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:38,763
No worries. I come prepared.

128
00:10:43,601 --> 00:10:44,725
Thank you.

129
00:10:45,395 --> 00:10:48,690
This will serve nicely as a bill of sale.

130
00:11:01,233 --> 00:11:02,287
Whoa.

131
00:11:06,499 --> 00:11:09,065
Now, as to you poor devils...

132
00:11:10,503 --> 00:11:11,754
So, as I see it,

133
00:11:12,338 --> 00:11:15,008
when it comes to the subject
of what to do next,

134
00:11:15,383 --> 00:11:17,886
you gentlemen have two choices.

135
00:11:18,469 --> 00:11:20,597
One. Once I'm gone,

136
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:23,641
you could lift that beast
off the remaining Speck,

137
00:11:23,725 --> 00:11:25,351
then carry him to the nearest town.

138
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:28,813
Which would be at least 37 miles
back the way you came.

139
00:11:29,522 --> 00:11:30,669
Or, two.

140
00:11:31,691 --> 00:11:33,234
You could unshackle yourselves...

141
00:11:33,985 --> 00:11:35,069
take that rifle,

142
00:11:35,445 --> 00:11:38,114
put a bullet in his head,
bury the two of them deep,

143
00:11:38,323 --> 00:11:41,367
and then make your way to a more
enlightened area of this country.

144
00:11:42,577 --> 00:11:43,578
Choice is yours.

145
00:11:43,953 --> 00:11:45,663
Oh, and on the off chance

146
00:11:45,747 --> 00:11:48,416
there are any astronomy aficionados
amongst you,

147
00:11:48,499 --> 00:11:50,919
the North Star is that one.

148
00:11:52,749 --> 00:11:53,755
Ta-ta!

149
00:11:55,050 --> 00:11:56,132
[clicks tongue]

150
00:12:09,062 --> 00:12:10,605
[chains clanking]

151
00:12:10,980 --> 00:12:14,234
Now, wait a minute, fellas.
Let's talk about this.

152
00:12:18,655 --> 00:12:21,741
You gotta be reasonable
in a situation like this.

153
00:12:23,409 --> 00:12:26,412
I'm not a bad guy. I'm just doing my job.

154
00:12:26,788 --> 00:12:29,958
Blueberry, didn't I give you
my last apple?

155
00:12:30,625 --> 00:12:31,751
Tell you what, boys.

156
00:12:31,834 --> 00:12:34,879
Take me to the doc in El Paso, I'll get
you your freedom.

157
00:12:35,338 --> 00:12:37,423
-[gun cocks]
-[Dicky] No. No, please.

158
00:13:24,743 --> 00:13:25,763
All right, now.

159
00:13:26,556 --> 00:13:28,558
I'd like you to take
two of these, tonight.

160
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:30,476
-[coughs]
-And then, in the morning...

161
00:13:33,104 --> 00:13:34,355
There's a nigger on the horse!

162
00:14:00,340 --> 00:14:01,716
What's everybody staring at?

163
00:14:02,508 --> 00:14:04,469
They ain't never seen no nigger
on no horse, before.

164
00:14:06,721 --> 00:14:09,515
[goats bleating]

165
00:14:16,962 --> 00:14:18,024
Whoa.

166
00:14:28,076 --> 00:14:29,786
Good morning, innkeeper.

167
00:14:31,704 --> 00:14:33,915
Two beers for two weary travelers.

168
00:14:34,123 --> 00:14:38,044
It's still a bit early.
We won't be open for another hour.

169
00:14:38,795 --> 00:14:40,380
By then, we'll be serving breakfast.

170
00:14:41,714 --> 00:14:43,091
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

171
00:14:44,008 --> 00:14:45,802
What the hell you think you're doing, boy?

172
00:14:46,219 --> 00:14:47,720
Get that nigger out of here.

173
00:14:53,309 --> 00:14:54,977
[innkeeper] Help! Help!

174
00:14:55,061 --> 00:14:55,978
[Schultz] Innkeeper!

175
00:14:56,396 --> 00:14:59,315
Remember, get the sheriff,
not the marshal.

176
00:14:59,941 --> 00:15:01,359
[innkeeper] <i>Sheriff! Help!</i>

177
00:15:01,734 --> 00:15:02,735
Alas.

178
00:15:04,612 --> 00:15:06,697
Now, we must act as our own bartender.

179
00:15:09,492 --> 00:15:10,785
Sit down, my boy.

180
00:15:21,087 --> 00:15:23,047
-What kind of dentist are you?
-[chuckles]

181
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:29,053
Despite that cart, I haven't
practiced dentistry in five years.

182
00:15:33,975 --> 00:15:36,310
But these days,
I practice a new profession.

183
00:15:39,439 --> 00:15:40,487
Bounty hunter.

184
00:15:47,321 --> 00:15:48,739
Do you know what a bounty hunter is?

185
00:15:49,529 --> 00:15:50,533
No.

186
00:15:50,950 --> 00:15:51,951
Well...

187
00:15:53,786 --> 00:15:57,582
The way the slave trade
deals in human lives for cash,

188
00:15:58,040 --> 00:16:00,001
a bounty hunter deals in corpses.

189
00:16:00,877 --> 00:16:02,378
[clicking tongue] Hat.

190
00:16:06,674 --> 00:16:07,675
<i>Prost.</i>

191
00:16:16,434 --> 00:16:18,978
The state places a bounty on a man's head.

192
00:16:19,103 --> 00:16:22,106
I track that man, I find that man,
I kill that man.

193
00:16:22,190 --> 00:16:26,068
After I've killed him, I transport
that man's corpse back to the authorities.

194
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:28,613
Sometimes that's easier said than done.

195
00:16:28,946 --> 00:16:31,949
I show that corpse to the authorities,
proving yes, indeed,

196
00:16:32,033 --> 00:16:36,204
I truly have killed him, at which point,
the authorities pay me the bounty.

197
00:16:36,871 --> 00:16:40,291
So, like slavery,
it's a flesh-for-cash business.

198
00:16:41,840 --> 00:16:42,919
What's a bounty?

199
00:16:46,881 --> 00:16:48,132
It's like a reward.

200
00:16:48,883 --> 00:16:51,302
You kill people
and they give you a reward?

201
00:16:52,303 --> 00:16:53,638
Certain people, yeah.

202
00:16:54,222 --> 00:16:55,848
-Bad people?
-Ah!

203
00:16:56,432 --> 00:16:58,309
Badder they are, bigger the reward.

204
00:16:59,477 --> 00:17:00,770
Which brings me to you.

205
00:17:01,854 --> 00:17:05,107
And I must admit, I'm at a bit
of a quandary when it comes to you.

206
00:17:06,526 --> 00:17:08,694
On one hand, I despise slavery.

207
00:17:08,986 --> 00:17:12,114
On the other hand, I need your help.

208
00:17:12,198 --> 00:17:14,742
If you're not in a position
to refuse, all the better.

209
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:20,498
So for the time being, I'm gonna make
this slavery malarkey work to my benefit.

210
00:17:21,457 --> 00:17:23,709
Still, having said that...

211
00:17:25,002 --> 00:17:26,066
I feel guilty.

212
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:32,969
So, I would like the two of us
to enter into an agreement.

213
00:17:40,309 --> 00:17:41,936
I'm looking for the Brittle brothers.

214
00:17:46,816 --> 00:17:50,027
However, at this endeavor,
I'm at a slight disadvantage,

215
00:17:50,861 --> 00:17:52,738
insofar as I don't know
what they look like.

216
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:57,243
But you do. Don't you?

217
00:17:57,994 --> 00:17:59,495
I know what they look like, all right.

218
00:18:00,162 --> 00:18:01,202
Good.

219
00:18:01,706 --> 00:18:02,957
So, here's my agreement.

220
00:18:03,916 --> 00:18:05,876
You travel with me until we find them.

221
00:18:05,960 --> 00:18:07,211
-Where we going?
-Ah,

222
00:18:07,295 --> 00:18:10,089
I hear at least two of them
are overseeing up in Gatlinburg,

223
00:18:10,172 --> 00:18:11,299
but I don't know where.

224
00:18:12,466 --> 00:18:16,929
That means we visit every plantation
in Gatlinburg till we find them.

225
00:18:17,054 --> 00:18:18,180
And when we find them...

226
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:21,726
you point them out, and I kill them.

227
00:18:23,436 --> 00:18:24,500
You do that?

228
00:18:25,187 --> 00:18:29,275
I agree to give you your freedom.
25 dollars per Brittle brother,

229
00:18:29,358 --> 00:18:31,152
-that's 75 dollars.
-[chatter outside]

230
00:18:31,235 --> 00:18:34,739
And, as if on cue, here comes the sheriff.

231
00:18:42,496 --> 00:18:45,416
Okay, boys. Fun's over.

232
00:18:46,890 --> 00:18:47,918
Come on out.

233
00:18:50,504 --> 00:18:51,547
[indistinct chatter]]

234
00:18:51,631 --> 00:18:54,884
All right, folks. Calm down.

235
00:18:56,260 --> 00:18:57,595
Go about your business.

236
00:18:59,096 --> 00:19:00,806
These jokers'll be gone, soon.

237
00:19:03,267 --> 00:19:07,688
Now, why y'all wanna come
into my town and start trouble?

238
00:19:09,565 --> 00:19:11,859
Scare all these nice people!

239
00:19:13,152 --> 00:19:15,446
You ain't got nothing better to do

240
00:19:16,155 --> 00:19:21,911
than to come into Bill Sharp's town
and show your ass?

241
00:19:22,620 --> 00:19:24,372
-[gunshot]
-[sheriff screams]

242
00:19:24,497 --> 00:19:26,540
[Sheriff groans]

243
00:19:26,624 --> 00:19:27,875
[woman screams]

244
00:19:30,169 --> 00:19:31,962
[man] What'd you just do to our sheriff?

245
00:19:36,634 --> 00:19:38,177
-[gunshot]
-[woman gasps]

246
00:19:38,386 --> 00:19:40,763
[crowd screaming]

247
00:19:45,393 --> 00:19:46,936
Now, you can get the marshal.

248
00:19:49,146 --> 00:19:51,524
[innkeeper] Marshal! Marshal!

249
00:19:51,607 --> 00:19:53,734
-[Schultz] Should we wait inside?
-Can't we just leave?

250
00:19:53,859 --> 00:19:54,898
After you.

251
00:19:57,571 --> 00:20:00,991
Move that buckboard a long ways
across the street from the saloon.

252
00:20:01,992 --> 00:20:04,161
I want six men, six rifles behind it.

253
00:20:04,954 --> 00:20:07,331
I want two men, two rifles
up on this roof,

254
00:20:07,415 --> 00:20:09,041
two men, two rifles on that roof.

255
00:20:09,750 --> 00:20:11,877
All the barrels aimed at that front door.

256
00:20:13,170 --> 00:20:15,840
Somebody get poor Bill out of the goddamn
street.

257
00:20:16,924 --> 00:20:18,134
You, in the saloon!

258
00:20:19,635 --> 00:20:22,346
We got 100 rifles aimed
at every way out of that building.

259
00:20:23,597 --> 00:20:26,058
You got one chance
to get out of this alive.

260
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:30,438
You and your nigger come out, right now,
with your hands over your head

261
00:20:30,521 --> 00:20:31,605
and I mean right now!

262
00:20:33,107 --> 00:20:36,736
[Schultz] <i>Is this the marshal</i>
<i>I have the pleasure of addressing?</i>

263
00:20:37,234 --> 00:20:38,279
Yes, it is.

264
00:20:39,029 --> 00:20:40,823
This is U.S. Marshal Gill Tatum.

265
00:20:41,282 --> 00:20:42,950
[Schultz] Na, wunderbar, <i>marshal.</i>

266
00:20:43,993 --> 00:20:47,288
I have relieved myself of all weapons,

267
00:20:47,997 --> 00:20:53,419
and, just as you have instructed,
I am ready to step outside

268
00:20:53,794 --> 00:20:57,298
with my hands raised above my head.

269
00:20:58,841 --> 00:21:01,427
<i>I trust, as a representative</i>

270
00:21:01,510 --> 00:21:04,889
of the criminal justice system
of the United States of America,

271
00:21:05,097 --> 00:21:10,853
I shan't be shot down in the street
by either you or your deputies

272
00:21:11,061 --> 00:21:13,522
before I've had my day in court.

273
00:21:14,148 --> 00:21:15,691
You mean, like you did our sheriff?

274
00:21:16,317 --> 00:21:18,277
Shot him down like a dog in the street!

275
00:21:18,444 --> 00:21:20,571
Yes, that's exactly what I mean.

276
00:21:20,905 --> 00:21:22,907
Do I have your word, as a lawman,

277
00:21:22,990 --> 00:21:26,327
not to shoot me down
like a dog in the street?

278
00:21:29,872 --> 00:21:33,375
Well, much as we'd all enjoy
seeing something like that,

279
00:21:33,459 --> 00:21:35,961
ain't nobody gonna cheat
the hangman in my town.

280
00:21:37,421 --> 00:21:39,673
Fair enough, marshal. Here we come.

281
00:21:42,218 --> 00:21:43,969
They're a little tense out there,

282
00:21:44,470 --> 00:21:47,723
so don't make any quick movements
and let me do the talking.

283
00:21:49,517 --> 00:21:51,018
-[door opening, closing]
-Come ahead.

284
00:21:58,067 --> 00:22:00,486
-You unarmed?
-[Schultz] Yes, indeed we are.

285
00:22:01,862 --> 00:22:04,114
Marshal Tatum, may I address you

286
00:22:04,198 --> 00:22:07,576
and your deputies, and apparently
the entire town of Daughtrey,

287
00:22:07,660 --> 00:22:09,578
as to the incident that just occurred?

288
00:22:11,247 --> 00:22:12,261
Go on.

289
00:22:12,665 --> 00:22:13,679
Thank you.

290
00:22:14,041 --> 00:22:16,210
My name is Dr. King Schultz.

291
00:22:16,293 --> 00:22:19,338
Like yourself, marshal,
I'm a servant of the court.

292
00:22:19,672 --> 00:22:23,008
The man lying dead in the dirt,
who the good people of Daughtrey

293
00:22:23,092 --> 00:22:27,304
saw fit to elect as their sheriff,
who went by the name of Bill Sharp,

294
00:22:27,471 --> 00:22:31,433
is actually a wanted outlaw
by the name of Willard Peck

295
00:22:32,142 --> 00:22:34,687
with a price on his head of 200 dollars.

296
00:22:34,937 --> 00:22:37,398
Now, that's 200 dollars, dead or alive.

297
00:22:38,107 --> 00:22:39,191
The hell you say?

298
00:22:39,859 --> 00:22:43,279
I'm aware this is probably
disconcerting news,

299
00:22:43,779 --> 00:22:45,239
but I'm willing to wager

300
00:22:45,322 --> 00:22:49,118
this man was elected sheriff
at some time in the past two years?

301
00:22:50,828 --> 00:22:52,288
-Yeah.
-[Schultz] I know this

302
00:22:52,371 --> 00:22:55,082
because three years ago,
he was rustling cattle

303
00:22:55,165 --> 00:22:58,627
from the B.C. Corrigan Cattle Company
of Lubbock, Texas.

304
00:22:59,128 --> 00:23:01,630
Now, this is a warrant

305
00:23:02,006 --> 00:23:08,095
made out by circuit court judge
Henry Allen Laudermilk of Austin, Texas.

306
00:23:08,721 --> 00:23:10,389
You're encouraged to wire him.

307
00:23:10,598 --> 00:23:15,436
He'll back up who I am
and who your dear departed sheriff was.

308
00:23:23,694 --> 00:23:25,070
In other words, marshal...

309
00:23:25,946 --> 00:23:27,281
you owe me 200 dollars.

310
00:23:28,198 --> 00:23:32,912
["Lo Chiamavano King (His Name Is King)"
by Luis Bacalov & Edda Dell'Orso playing]

311
00:23:36,415 --> 00:23:37,416
I'll be damned.

312
00:23:37,875 --> 00:23:42,463
♪ <i>His name was King</i>
<i>He had a horse ♪</i>

313
00:23:43,005 --> 00:23:47,301
♪ <i>Along the countryside</i>
<i>I saw him ride ♪</i>

314
00:23:47,968 --> 00:23:52,264
♪ <i>He had a gun</i>
<i>I knew him well ♪</i>

315
00:23:52,723 --> 00:23:57,895
♪ <i>Oh, I heard him singing</i>
<i>I knew he loved someone ♪</i>

316
00:24:06,028 --> 00:24:08,364
[Schultz] After this Brittle business
is behind us...

317
00:24:09,740 --> 00:24:11,033
you'll be a free man.

318
00:24:11,742 --> 00:24:15,120
With a horse,
75 dollars in your back pocket...

319
00:24:17,998 --> 00:24:19,291
What's your plan after that?

320
00:24:21,752 --> 00:24:22,753
Find my wife...

321
00:24:24,254 --> 00:24:25,255
and buy her freedom.

322
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:28,884
Django!

323
00:24:30,094 --> 00:24:32,221
I had no idea you were a married man.

324
00:24:33,430 --> 00:24:35,265
Do most slaves believe in marriage?

325
00:24:36,892 --> 00:24:38,018
Me and my wife do.

326
00:24:39,395 --> 00:24:43,065
Old Man Carrucan didn't.
That's why we... ran off.

327
00:24:44,817 --> 00:24:45,943
[Carrucan] Django...

328
00:24:46,819 --> 00:24:48,946
Django, Django...

329
00:24:49,697 --> 00:24:51,824
You got sand, Django.

330
00:24:53,158 --> 00:24:54,785
The boy's got sand.

331
00:24:56,912 --> 00:24:59,832
I got no use for a nigger with sand.

332
00:25:01,583 --> 00:25:04,628
I want you to burn a runaway "R"
right here on his cheek.

333
00:25:05,421 --> 00:25:06,463
And the girl, too.

334
00:25:06,714 --> 00:25:07,965
[Django sighs]

335
00:25:08,382 --> 00:25:12,970
And I want you to take them
to the Greenville auction and sell them.

336
00:25:13,918 --> 00:25:15,014
Both of them.

337
00:25:16,348 --> 00:25:17,516
Separately.

338
00:25:20,477 --> 00:25:21,478
And this one...

339
00:25:24,189 --> 00:25:26,567
You will sell him cheap.

340
00:25:29,111 --> 00:25:30,154
[Schultz] In Greenville...

341
00:25:33,198 --> 00:25:35,743
there should be some sort
of a records office.

342
00:25:43,292 --> 00:25:44,960
You know, when she was sold...

343
00:25:46,962 --> 00:25:48,714
you know where she came from...

344
00:25:50,174 --> 00:25:51,341
and you know her name.

345
00:25:52,760 --> 00:25:53,849
What is her name?

346
00:25:54,720 --> 00:25:55,763
Broomhilda.

347
00:25:57,723 --> 00:25:58,724
What?

348
00:25:58,849 --> 00:26:00,017
Broomhilda.

349
00:26:01,143 --> 00:26:02,269
Broomhilda?

350
00:26:05,355 --> 00:26:06,565
Were her owners German?

351
00:26:07,024 --> 00:26:08,088
Yeah, how you know?

352
00:26:09,109 --> 00:26:10,819
She wasn't born
on the Carrucan plantation.

353
00:26:10,903 --> 00:26:13,238
She was raised
by a German mistress. The Von Shafts.

354
00:26:13,405 --> 00:26:14,740
She speak a little German, too.

355
00:26:15,574 --> 00:26:17,910
-Your wife?
-Mm-hmm. When she was little,

356
00:26:17,993 --> 00:26:20,662
her mistress taught her, so she'd have
someone to speak German with.

357
00:26:22,581 --> 00:26:24,041
Well, let me get this straight.

358
00:26:25,334 --> 00:26:29,963
Your slave wife speaks German
and her name is Broomhilda Von Shaft?

359
00:26:30,047 --> 00:26:31,061
Yep.

360
00:26:35,511 --> 00:26:36,678
They call me Hildi.

361
00:26:46,522 --> 00:26:48,607
[rooster crowing]

362
00:26:54,863 --> 00:27:00,077
When we gain access to these plantations,
we'll be putting on an act.

363
00:27:01,787 --> 00:27:03,997
You'll be playing a character.

364
00:27:11,252 --> 00:27:12,256
Huh?

365
00:27:13,271 --> 00:27:14,299
No?

366
00:27:21,682 --> 00:27:25,727
Now, during the act,
you can never break character.

367
00:27:27,396 --> 00:27:28,419
Do you understand?

368
00:27:29,481 --> 00:27:31,525
Yeah. Don't break character.

369
00:27:34,403 --> 00:27:37,739
And your character is that of the valet.

370
00:27:38,866 --> 00:27:39,867
What that is?

371
00:27:41,493 --> 00:27:43,203
That's a fancy word for servant.

372
00:27:44,037 --> 00:27:45,289
-Valet?
-Mm-hmm.

373
00:27:45,372 --> 00:27:46,436
[Django chuckles]

374
00:27:46,874 --> 00:27:50,752
And now, Django, you may choose
your character's costume.

375
00:27:53,630 --> 00:27:55,549
Youse gonna let me pick out
my own clothes?

376
00:27:55,688 --> 00:27:56,758
But of course.

377
00:27:57,426 --> 00:28:00,929
["Lo Chiamavano King (His Name Is King)"
by Luis Bacalov & Edda Dell'Orso playing]

378
00:28:01,013 --> 00:28:03,807
-♪ <i>His name was King ♪</i>
-♪ <i>His name was King ♪</i>

379
00:28:03,891 --> 00:28:06,310
-♪ <i>He had a horse ♪</i>
-♪ <i>He had a brother ♪</i>

380
00:28:06,393 --> 00:28:11,231
♪ <i>Along the countryside</i>
<i>I saw him ride ♪</i>

381
00:28:11,815 --> 00:28:15,903
♪ <i>He had a gun</i>
<i>Oh, I knew him well ♪</i>

382
00:28:16,570 --> 00:28:18,655
♪ <i>And when he shot ♪</i>

383
00:28:19,281 --> 00:28:23,202
♪ <i>Oh, that man, he never missed ♪</i>

384
00:28:23,660 --> 00:28:25,412
♪ <i>Ride on, King, ride ♪</i>

385
00:28:25,495 --> 00:28:26,413
[Schultz] Whoa.

386
00:28:26,538 --> 00:28:29,124
♪ <i>You get your man ♪</i>

387
00:28:30,751 --> 00:28:34,546
It's against the law for niggers
to ride horses in this territory.

388
00:28:34,838 --> 00:28:37,382
This is my valet. My valet does not walk.

389
00:28:38,300 --> 00:28:40,594
I said, niggers on horses--

390
00:28:40,677 --> 00:28:44,890
His name is Django. He's a free man.
He can ride what he pleases.

391
00:28:45,224 --> 00:28:48,477
Not on my property.
Not around my niggers, he can't.

392
00:28:49,561 --> 00:28:50,687
My good sir!

393
00:28:51,980 --> 00:28:53,815
Perhaps we got off on the wrong boot.

394
00:28:54,441 --> 00:28:56,735
Allow me to unring this bell.

395
00:28:57,194 --> 00:29:00,948
My name is Dr. King Schultz,
this is my valet, Django,

396
00:29:01,156 --> 00:29:03,408
and these are our horses, Tony and Fritz.

397
00:29:03,492 --> 00:29:05,327
-[Fritz snorts]
-[women laughing]

398
00:29:07,162 --> 00:29:13,335
Mr. Bennett, I've been led to believe
that you're a gentleman and a businessman.

399
00:29:13,418 --> 00:29:17,005
And it is for these attributes
we've ridden from Texas to Tennessee

400
00:29:17,089 --> 00:29:18,632
to parley with you, now.

401
00:29:20,092 --> 00:29:23,345
I wish to purchase
one of your nigger gals.

402
00:29:25,555 --> 00:29:29,101
You and your Jimmie
rode from Texas to Tennessee

403
00:29:29,184 --> 00:29:30,769
to buy one of my nigger gals?

404
00:29:30,978 --> 00:29:32,229
No appointment, no nothing?

405
00:29:33,021 --> 00:29:34,314
Oh, I'm afraid so.

406
00:29:35,148 --> 00:29:37,317
Well, what if I was to say
I don't like you

407
00:29:37,693 --> 00:29:41,238
or your fancy-pants nigger,
and I wouldn't sell you a tinker's damn?

408
00:29:42,030 --> 00:29:43,490
Now, what you got to say about that?

409
00:29:46,994 --> 00:29:48,203
Mr. Bennett...

410
00:29:49,329 --> 00:29:52,374
if you are the businessman
I've been led to believe you to be,

411
00:29:52,749 --> 00:29:57,296
I have 5,000 things I might say
that could change your mind.

412
00:29:58,920 --> 00:29:59,965
[chuckles]

413
00:30:01,925 --> 00:30:05,262
Well, come on inside
and get yourself something cool to drink.

414
00:30:06,555 --> 00:30:07,973
Huh! Mm-hmm.

415
00:30:10,017 --> 00:30:11,018
[chuckles]

416
00:30:17,774 --> 00:30:19,735
[indistinct chatter]

417
00:30:19,818 --> 00:30:21,903
Maybe while we discuss business,

418
00:30:21,987 --> 00:30:24,531
you could provide
one of your loveliest black creatures

419
00:30:24,614 --> 00:30:27,367
to escort Django, here,
around your magnificent grounds.

420
00:30:27,451 --> 00:30:29,536
[Big Daddy] Oh, well, absolutely. Betina?

421
00:30:29,661 --> 00:30:32,914
-Yes, sir, Big Daddy?
-Uh... What's your Jimmie's name, again?

422
00:30:33,457 --> 00:30:34,833
-Django.
-Django!

423
00:30:35,125 --> 00:30:37,544
Betina, sugar, could you take Django there

424
00:30:37,627 --> 00:30:40,797
and take him around the grounds, here,
and show him all the pretty stuff?

425
00:30:41,006 --> 00:30:43,175
-As you please, Big Daddy.
-Oh, Mr. Bennett.

426
00:30:43,884 --> 00:30:48,430
I must remind you, Django is a free man.
He cannot be treated like a slave.

427
00:30:48,555 --> 00:30:50,015
Within the bounds of good taste,

428
00:30:50,098 --> 00:30:52,309
he must be treated
as an extension of myself.

429
00:30:52,851 --> 00:30:54,686
[Big Daddy] Understood, Schultz.
Betina, sugar?

430
00:30:54,770 --> 00:30:57,647
-Yes'm?
-Django isn't a slave.

431
00:30:58,315 --> 00:31:00,400
Django is a free man, you understand?

432
00:31:01,651 --> 00:31:04,154
You can't treat him like any
of the other niggers around here,

433
00:31:04,237 --> 00:31:07,074
because he ain't like any of the other
niggers around here. You got it?

434
00:31:07,366 --> 00:31:09,993
You want I should treat him
like white folks?

435
00:31:10,369 --> 00:31:11,383
No.

436
00:31:12,079 --> 00:31:13,246
That's not what I said.

437
00:31:13,580 --> 00:31:15,457
Then I don't know
what you want, Big Daddy.

438
00:31:16,416 --> 00:31:19,878
[Big Daddy] Yes, I can see that. Uh...

439
00:31:21,463 --> 00:31:23,715
What's the name of that
peckawood boy from town

440
00:31:23,799 --> 00:31:25,092
that works with the glass?

441
00:31:26,009 --> 00:31:27,761
His mama work over at the lumberyard.

442
00:31:28,220 --> 00:31:30,889
-Oh, you mean Jerry.
-That's the boy's name. Jerry.

443
00:31:31,098 --> 00:31:33,683
-You know Jerry, don't you, sugar?
-Yes'm, Big Daddy.

444
00:31:34,101 --> 00:31:35,268
Well, that's it, then!

445
00:31:36,061 --> 00:31:38,313
You just treat him like you would Jerry.

446
00:31:38,980 --> 00:31:45,320
[plays classical violin]

447
00:31:45,570 --> 00:31:48,532
That house we just left from
is the Big House.

448
00:31:48,782 --> 00:31:51,243
Big Daddy call it that because it's big.

449
00:31:52,702 --> 00:31:54,955
That there is the pantry.

450
00:31:55,205 --> 00:31:57,791
That's where Big Daddy
hang all his dead meat.

451
00:31:58,750 --> 00:32:00,210
Poor little squirrels.

452
00:32:02,421 --> 00:32:04,089
What you do for your master?

453
00:32:05,173 --> 00:32:07,008
Didn't you hear him tell you
I ain't no slave?

454
00:32:07,092 --> 00:32:09,386
-So, you really free?
-Yes, I's free.

455
00:32:09,594 --> 00:32:11,596
You mean you wanna dress like that?

456
00:32:13,932 --> 00:32:16,393
-Betina, I need to ask something.
-What you want?

457
00:32:16,476 --> 00:32:19,688
I'm looking for three white men.
Three brothers. Overseers.

458
00:32:19,771 --> 00:32:22,149
-Their name is Brittle. You know them?
-Brittle?

459
00:32:22,232 --> 00:32:24,860
Yes, Brittle.
John Brittle, Ellis Brittle...

460
00:32:25,277 --> 00:32:27,779
Roger Brittle, sometime called Little Raj.

461
00:32:28,113 --> 00:32:29,114
I don't know them.

462
00:32:30,282 --> 00:32:31,825
They could be using a different name.

463
00:32:32,159 --> 00:32:35,787
-They would've come this past year.
-You mean the Shaffers?

464
00:32:36,288 --> 00:32:38,165
Maybe. Three brothers?

465
00:32:38,498 --> 00:32:40,250
-Uh-huh.
-They here?

466
00:32:40,584 --> 00:32:43,086
-Uh-huh.
-Could you point one of them out to me?

467
00:32:43,670 --> 00:32:45,714
Well, one's over in that field.

468
00:32:50,844 --> 00:32:53,722
["Freedom" by Anthony Hamilton
& Elayna Boynton playing]

469
00:32:54,014 --> 00:32:55,265
♪ <i>Ooh ♪</i>

470
00:32:59,311 --> 00:33:01,605
[Django] Old Man Carrucan
ain't gonna appreciate this, now.

471
00:33:01,730 --> 00:33:04,149
She work in the house, John.
You mess the skin up,

472
00:33:04,399 --> 00:33:06,818
you gonna mess her up,
she ain't gonna be worth a damn thing.

473
00:33:07,068 --> 00:33:08,195
Now, your Bible say...

474
00:33:09,070 --> 00:33:14,075
♪ <i>Felt like the weight of the</i>
<i>World was on my shoulders ♪</i>

475
00:33:14,159 --> 00:33:15,702
[Django] I told you, I made her do it.

476
00:33:16,119 --> 00:33:18,872
-You ready?
-She didn't wanna run off with me.

477
00:33:18,955 --> 00:33:21,750
If anybody should be getting whupped,
it should be me, John.

478
00:33:21,833 --> 00:33:24,628
I've been here long enough.
You've known me a long time, now.

479
00:33:25,059 --> 00:33:26,087
[dogs barking]

480
00:33:26,171 --> 00:33:31,885
♪ <i>Facing the fear that</i>
<i>The truth I discover ♪</i>

481
00:33:34,221 --> 00:33:36,348
You know, Master Carrucan
ain't gonna appreciate this.

482
00:33:37,098 --> 00:33:38,141
She's a house slave.

483
00:33:39,601 --> 00:33:41,728
-[whipping]
-[screams]

484
00:33:41,811 --> 00:33:46,149
♪ <i>I'm looking for freedom ♪</i>

485
00:33:46,441 --> 00:33:48,652
♪ <i>Looking for freedom ♪</i>

486
00:33:48,902 --> 00:33:50,862
♪ <i>Oh, oh, oh ♪</i>

487
00:33:50,987 --> 00:33:53,949
♪ <i>And to find it</i>
<i>Cost me everything I have ♪</i>

488
00:33:54,032 --> 00:33:56,743
-[whipping]
-[screams]

489
00:33:58,537 --> 00:34:00,330
♪ <i>Well, I am looking for freedom ♪</i>

490
00:34:00,747 --> 00:34:02,624
-[whipping]
-[Django] I'm asking you, please.

491
00:34:02,832 --> 00:34:05,627
Ain't this what you want? I'm keeping it
funny for you. Now, John, please.

492
00:34:05,710 --> 00:34:07,087
-[whipping]
-[groans]

493
00:34:07,170 --> 00:34:09,965
-♪ <i>Oh, and to find it ♪</i>
-Oh, God, oh, God, oh, God...

494
00:34:11,466 --> 00:34:12,676
I's on my knees, John.

495
00:34:13,176 --> 00:34:14,886
I like the way you beg, boy.

496
00:34:18,890 --> 00:34:20,517
Is that who you was looking for?

497
00:34:22,725 --> 00:34:23,770
Yep.

498
00:34:25,313 --> 00:34:26,398
Where the other two at?

499
00:34:26,731 --> 00:34:30,694
They by the stable,
punishing Little Jody for breaking eggs.

500
00:34:30,944 --> 00:34:32,070
They whipping Little Jody?

501
00:34:33,029 --> 00:34:34,406
Point me in that direction.

502
00:34:35,407 --> 00:34:38,326
You go to that tree
and keep going thattaway.

503
00:34:43,290 --> 00:34:45,000
Go get that white man I came here with.

504
00:34:47,002 --> 00:34:49,004
-[Little Raj] Come on, now.
-[Jody] No, no, please!

505
00:34:49,087 --> 00:34:50,547
[Little Raj] Come on, girlie. Come on.

506
00:34:50,630 --> 00:34:52,716
-[Jody sobs]
-[Little Raj] Get you set up, now.

507
00:34:53,049 --> 00:34:56,052
-And the Lord said, "The fear of ye..."
-[whipping]

508
00:34:56,511 --> 00:35:00,932
"...and the dread of ye
shall be on every beast of the earth."

509
00:35:01,016 --> 00:35:01,975
[whipping]

510
00:35:02,100 --> 00:35:04,227
-[Little Raj] Hey, give me that arm!
-[Jody] Please, no!

511
00:35:04,311 --> 00:35:07,022
[Little Raj] You better give me that arm.
You better give me that arm!

512
00:35:23,788 --> 00:35:25,290
Okay, she ready!

513
00:35:26,875 --> 00:35:28,793
[Jody whimpers]

514
00:35:39,929 --> 00:35:40,930
And after this...

515
00:35:41,723 --> 00:35:43,725
we'll see if you break eggs again.

516
00:35:47,228 --> 00:35:48,229
John Brittle!

517
00:36:09,751 --> 00:36:10,794
You remember me?

518
00:36:15,162 --> 00:36:16,216
[girl gasps]

519
00:36:23,723 --> 00:36:25,433
I like the way you die, boy.

520
00:36:31,439 --> 00:36:33,817
Goddamn son of a bitch!

521
00:36:41,574 --> 00:36:42,742
[grunts]

522
00:36:52,001 --> 00:36:53,336
Keep it funny!

523
00:36:57,340 --> 00:36:59,008
[screams]

524
00:37:08,268 --> 00:37:09,561
[Little Raj groans]

525
00:37:19,112 --> 00:37:20,196
Y'all wanna see something?

526
00:37:20,953 --> 00:37:22,031
[cocks gun]

527
00:37:23,199 --> 00:37:24,743
[Little Raj groans] No!

528
00:37:25,243 --> 00:37:26,619
-[groans]
-[gunfire]

529
00:37:30,206 --> 00:37:31,416
[cocks gun]

530
00:37:35,879 --> 00:37:36,943
Who were they?

531
00:37:38,298 --> 00:37:40,633
That's Big John, that's Little Raj.

532
00:37:41,301 --> 00:37:42,415
Where's Ellis?

533
00:37:42,886 --> 00:37:45,263
He's the one hightailing it
across that field right now.

534
00:37:50,185 --> 00:37:51,436
-You sure that's him?
-Yeah.

535
00:37:51,811 --> 00:37:53,438
-Positive?
-I don't know.

536
00:37:53,897 --> 00:37:56,191
-If you're positive?
-I don't know what "positive" mean.

537
00:37:56,274 --> 00:37:57,692
-It means you're sure.
-Yes.

538
00:37:57,817 --> 00:37:59,819
-"Yes," what?
-Yes, I'm sure that's Ellis Brittle.

539
00:38:13,124 --> 00:38:14,417
I'm positive he dead.

540
00:38:19,628 --> 00:38:20,715
Django!

541
00:38:22,801 --> 00:38:27,222
Everybody calm down.
We mean no-one else any harm.

542
00:38:27,680 --> 00:38:28,932
Who are you two jokers?

543
00:38:29,516 --> 00:38:32,352
I am Dr. King Schultz,
a legal representative

544
00:38:32,477 --> 00:38:35,814
of the criminal justice system
of the United States of America.

545
00:38:35,897 --> 00:38:39,275
The man to my left is Django Freeman.
He's my deputy.

546
00:38:40,068 --> 00:38:41,986
In my pocket is a warrant

547
00:38:42,237 --> 00:38:46,491
signed by circuit court judge
Henry Allen Laudermilk of Austin, Texas

548
00:38:46,699 --> 00:38:50,370
for the arrest and capture, dead or alive,

549
00:38:50,620 --> 00:38:55,375
of John Brittle,
Roger Brittle and Ellis Brittle.

550
00:38:55,583 --> 00:38:57,126
They were going by the name Shaffer.

551
00:38:59,170 --> 00:39:02,257
[Schultz] You know them by the name
of Shaffer, but the butchers' real name

552
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:03,354
was Brittle.

553
00:39:03,550 --> 00:39:06,886
These are wanted men.
The law wants them for murder.

554
00:39:07,095 --> 00:39:08,304
Now, I reiterate.

555
00:39:08,721 --> 00:39:11,391
The warrant states "dead or alive,"

556
00:39:11,474 --> 00:39:14,769
so when Mr. Freeman and myself
executed these men on sight,

557
00:39:14,978 --> 00:39:18,106
we were operating
within our legal boundaries.

558
00:39:19,148 --> 00:39:22,944
I realize passions are high...

559
00:39:24,028 --> 00:39:25,446
but I must warn you,

560
00:39:26,155 --> 00:39:29,284
the penalty for taking deadly force
against an officer of the court

561
00:39:29,367 --> 00:39:31,119
in the performance of his duty is...

562
00:39:32,036 --> 00:39:33,955
you'll be hung by the neck
until you're dead.

563
00:39:37,709 --> 00:39:42,046
Now, may I please remove the warrant
from my pocket so you may examine it?

564
00:39:44,465 --> 00:39:45,466
Gimme.

565
00:40:02,066 --> 00:40:03,067
Satisfied?

566
00:40:10,199 --> 00:40:11,826
May I have that back, please?

567
00:40:17,749 --> 00:40:18,958
Get off my land.

568
00:40:19,459 --> 00:40:20,877
Posthaste.

569
00:40:21,669 --> 00:40:25,632
Load up the bodies as quickly as you can,
and let's get out of here.

570
00:40:29,135 --> 00:40:31,387
[Schultz whistles]

571
00:40:51,783 --> 00:40:54,911
Yeah, that's them sons of bitches.

572
00:41:20,937 --> 00:41:23,856
[men shouting and whooping]

573
00:41:35,523 --> 00:41:36,619
[man 1] Come on, men!

574
00:41:38,705 --> 00:41:40,289
[man 2] We're coming for you, nigger!

575
00:41:51,801 --> 00:41:55,430
[Big Daddy] Now, unless they start
shooting first, nobody shoot them.

576
00:41:56,556 --> 00:41:58,349
That's way too simple for these jokers.

577
00:41:59,225 --> 00:42:01,853
We're gonna whup
that nigger-lover to death.

578
00:42:02,103 --> 00:42:06,357
And I'm gonna personally strip and clip
that garboon myself.

579
00:42:10,945 --> 00:42:11,990
Damn...

580
00:42:13,531 --> 00:42:15,742
I can't see fucking shit
out of this thing!

581
00:42:16,701 --> 00:42:18,161
[Randy] We ready or what?

582
00:42:18,786 --> 00:42:20,872
[Big Daddy] Hold on,
I'm fucking with my eyeholes.

583
00:42:21,330 --> 00:42:23,374
Oh. Oh, shit.

584
00:42:23,875 --> 00:42:25,793
I just made it worse.

585
00:42:25,877 --> 00:42:29,047
-[Harry] Who made this goddam shit?
-[O.B.] Willard's wife.

586
00:42:29,130 --> 00:42:31,090
[Willard] Well, make your own
goddamn masks!

587
00:42:31,174 --> 00:42:34,886
Look, nobody's saying they don't
appreciate what Jenny did.

588
00:42:34,969 --> 00:42:37,555
[Redfish] If all I had to do
was cut a hole in a bag,

589
00:42:37,722 --> 00:42:39,474
I could've cut it better than this.

590
00:42:39,682 --> 00:42:41,893
[Randy] What about you, Robert?
Can you see?

591
00:42:42,351 --> 00:42:43,644
[Robert] Not too good.

592
00:42:44,062 --> 00:42:48,191
I mean, if I don't move my head,
I can see you pretty good, more or less,

593
00:42:48,441 --> 00:42:51,861
but when I start riding, the bag's
moving all over, and I'm riding blind.

594
00:42:52,028 --> 00:42:52,904
Shit.

595
00:42:54,655 --> 00:42:56,157
I just made mine worse.

596
00:42:58,451 --> 00:42:59,911
Anybody bring any extra bags?

597
00:43:00,161 --> 00:43:03,164
[Redfish] No, nobody brought an extra bag!

598
00:43:03,456 --> 00:43:04,916
I'm just asking.

599
00:43:05,208 --> 00:43:07,001
[O.B.] Do we have to wear them
when we ride?

600
00:43:07,126 --> 00:43:08,252
Well, shitfire!

601
00:43:08,628 --> 00:43:11,589
If you don't wear them as you ride up,
that defeats the purpose!

602
00:43:11,672 --> 00:43:13,508
[Redfish] Well, I can't see
in this fucking thing!

603
00:43:13,716 --> 00:43:16,427
I can't breathe and I can't ride
in this fucking thing.

604
00:43:16,636 --> 00:43:18,638
[Willard] Well, fuck all y'all.
I'm going home.

605
00:43:19,263 --> 00:43:21,557
Now, I've watched my wife work all day,

606
00:43:21,641 --> 00:43:25,394
getting 30 bags together for you
ungrateful sons of bitches,

607
00:43:25,478 --> 00:43:28,940
and all I can hear is criticize,
criticize, criticize.

608
00:43:29,357 --> 00:43:32,276
From now on, don't ask me
or mine for nothing.

609
00:43:33,903 --> 00:43:36,781
Now, look. Let's not forget
why we're here.

610
00:43:36,948 --> 00:43:39,492
We got a killer nigger
over that hill, there.

611
00:43:40,159 --> 00:43:41,702
And we gotta make a lesson out of him.

612
00:43:41,786 --> 00:43:44,956
Okay, I'm confused.
Are the bags on or off?

613
00:43:45,706 --> 00:43:50,711
[Robert] I think we all think
the bag was a nice idea.

614
00:43:50,837 --> 00:43:53,589
-[Randy] Yeah.
-[Robert] But, not pointing any fingers...

615
00:43:54,507 --> 00:43:55,716
they could have been done better.

616
00:43:56,968 --> 00:44:00,012
So, how about no bags this time...

617
00:44:00,888 --> 00:44:05,768
but next time, we do the bags right,
and then we go full regalia.

618
00:44:05,852 --> 00:44:08,229
-[man 1] I like that idea.
-[man 2] You get my vote, brother.

619
00:44:08,312 --> 00:44:10,982
Wait a minute! I didn't say no bags.

620
00:44:11,649 --> 00:44:13,234
But nobody can see.

621
00:44:14,068 --> 00:44:16,779
-So?
-So, it'd be nice to see.

622
00:44:17,363 --> 00:44:22,076
Goddamn it, this is a raid!
I can't see, you can't see.

623
00:44:22,285 --> 00:44:25,413
So what? All that matters is,
can the fucking horse see?

624
00:44:25,746 --> 00:44:26,789
That's a raid!

625
00:44:27,373 --> 00:44:29,959
-[men shouting]
-[Harry] Sons of bitches!

626
00:44:31,043 --> 00:44:32,420
I can't see shit!

627
00:44:33,004 --> 00:44:36,382
[Big Daddy] There he is.
Get that nigger out from under that wagon.

628
00:44:37,425 --> 00:44:39,343
And get that nigger-lover
out of the wagon!

629
00:44:39,552 --> 00:44:41,929
-That nigger ain't down here, Big Daddy!
-What?

630
00:44:42,054 --> 00:44:43,764
-They tricked us.
-Where are they?

631
00:44:44,432 --> 00:44:45,433
<i>Auf Wiedersehen!</i>

632
00:44:51,189 --> 00:44:53,816
-Oh! [laughs]
-Bullseye.

633
00:44:54,609 --> 00:44:56,485
[men screaming]

634
00:44:57,069 --> 00:44:58,196
[Django] Look at them run.

635
00:45:03,326 --> 00:45:05,328
Yeah, cowards tend to do that.

636
00:45:14,045 --> 00:45:15,087
[Big Daddy] Goddamn it!

637
00:45:19,884 --> 00:45:20,968
Would you care to?

638
00:45:28,351 --> 00:45:29,977
[Big Daddy] Can't see shit out of this!

639
00:45:30,978 --> 00:45:32,521
-He's getting away.
-I got him.

640
00:45:34,899 --> 00:45:36,609
[Schultz] Big Daddy's getting away.

641
00:45:36,692 --> 00:45:37,751
I got him.

642
00:45:41,697 --> 00:45:43,366
[bullet whistling]

643
00:45:43,449 --> 00:45:44,742
[Big Daddy grunts]

644
00:45:53,125 --> 00:45:54,156
Got him.

645
00:45:56,462 --> 00:45:58,965
[horse neighing]

646
00:45:59,112 --> 00:46:00,132
[chuckles]

647
00:46:00,216 --> 00:46:01,676
The kid's a natural.

648
00:46:12,979 --> 00:46:15,106
How you know Broomhilda's
first masters was German?

649
00:46:16,941 --> 00:46:18,359
Broomhilda's a German name.

650
00:46:19,068 --> 00:46:21,487
If they named her, it stands
to reason they'd be German.

651
00:46:22,238 --> 00:46:24,073
Lots of gals where you're from
named Broomhilda?

652
00:46:25,199 --> 00:46:27,827
Broomhilda is the name of a character

653
00:46:28,244 --> 00:46:31,455
in the most popular
of all the German legends.

654
00:46:32,415 --> 00:46:33,791
There's a story about Broomhilda?

655
00:46:34,417 --> 00:46:35,543
Oh, yes, there is.

656
00:46:42,216 --> 00:46:43,252
Do you know it?

657
00:46:43,551 --> 00:46:45,344
Oh, every German knows that story.

658
00:46:52,101 --> 00:46:53,352
Would you like me to tell you?

659
00:46:54,760 --> 00:46:55,771
Well...

660
00:46:57,148 --> 00:47:00,776
Broomhilda was a... princess.

661
00:47:02,737 --> 00:47:06,657
She was a daughter of Wotan,
god of all gods.

662
00:47:07,908 --> 00:47:10,995
Anyway, her father is really mad at her.

663
00:47:11,287 --> 00:47:12,289
What she do?

664
00:47:13,664 --> 00:47:17,168
I can't exactly remember.
She disobeys him in some way.

665
00:47:18,127 --> 00:47:20,838
So, he puts her on top of the mountain.

666
00:47:21,672 --> 00:47:22,798
Broomhilda's on a mountain?

667
00:47:23,299 --> 00:47:26,635
It's a German legend, there's always going
to be a mountain in there somewhere.

668
00:47:27,511 --> 00:47:31,015
And he puts a fire-breathing dragon there,
to guard the mountain.

669
00:47:33,059 --> 00:47:37,855
And he surrounds her
in a circle of hellfire.

670
00:47:39,857 --> 00:47:43,694
And there, Broomhilda shall remain...

671
00:47:45,363 --> 00:47:50,368
unless a hero arises
brave enough to save her.

672
00:47:51,577 --> 00:47:52,912
Does a fella arise?

673
00:47:53,662 --> 00:47:56,123
Yes, Django. As a matter of fact, he does.

674
00:47:56,707 --> 00:47:58,501
A fella named Siegfried.

675
00:47:59,293 --> 00:48:00,378
Does Siegfried save her?

676
00:48:03,005 --> 00:48:04,632
Quite spectacularly so.

677
00:48:06,258 --> 00:48:10,179
He scales the mountain
because he's not afraid of it.

678
00:48:11,180 --> 00:48:14,141
He slays the dragon
because he's not afraid of him.

679
00:48:15,559 --> 00:48:17,561
And he walks through hellfire...

680
00:48:20,189 --> 00:48:22,024
because Broomhilda's worth it.

681
00:48:26,695 --> 00:48:27,822
I know how he feel.

682
00:48:29,824 --> 00:48:32,284
I think I'm just starting to realize that.

683
00:48:38,165 --> 00:48:42,086
Now, look... Django...

684
00:48:45,464 --> 00:48:48,926
I don't doubt that, one day,
you'll save your lady love.

685
00:48:50,344 --> 00:48:53,472
But I can't let you go to Greenville
in a good conscience.

686
00:48:55,266 --> 00:48:59,228
A slave auction town in Mississippi
isn't a place for you to visit.

687
00:48:59,770 --> 00:49:02,022
Free or not, it's just too dangerous.

688
00:49:05,693 --> 00:49:07,111
But let me ask you a question.

689
00:49:15,077 --> 00:49:17,079
How do you like
the bounty hunting business?

690
00:49:19,290 --> 00:49:21,041
Kill white folks and they pay you for it?

691
00:49:22,418 --> 00:49:23,419
What's not to like?

692
00:49:23,794 --> 00:49:25,880
Now, I have to admit, we make a good team.

693
00:49:26,464 --> 00:49:29,008
I thought you was mad at me
for killing Big John and Little Raj.

694
00:49:29,425 --> 00:49:31,635
Yeah, on that occasion,
you were a tad overzealous,

695
00:49:31,719 --> 00:49:33,179
but normally, that's a good thing.

696
00:49:34,638 --> 00:49:36,432
How'd you like to partner up
for the winter?

697
00:49:36,974 --> 00:49:38,184
What you mean, "partner up"?

698
00:49:39,185 --> 00:49:42,730
You work with me through the winter
till the snow melts...

699
00:49:44,315 --> 00:49:46,317
I give you a third of my bounties.

700
00:49:47,526 --> 00:49:51,155
So, we make some money this winter,
and when the snow melts...

701
00:49:52,072 --> 00:49:53,991
I'll take you to Greenville myself...

702
00:49:54,992 --> 00:49:57,369
and we'll find where they sent your wife.

703
00:50:02,249 --> 00:50:03,584
Why you care what happen to me?

704
00:50:05,711 --> 00:50:07,171
Why you care if I find my wife?

705
00:50:07,922 --> 00:50:08,957
Frankly...

706
00:50:10,716 --> 00:50:14,595
I've never given anybody
their freedom before, and now that I have,

707
00:50:14,678 --> 00:50:17,014
I feel vaguely responsible for you.

708
00:50:18,557 --> 00:50:20,684
Plus, when a German meets
a real-life Siegfried,

709
00:50:20,768 --> 00:50:21,977
that's kind of a big deal.

710
00:50:24,855 --> 00:50:26,982
As a German, I'm obliged to help you

711
00:50:27,066 --> 00:50:29,902
on your quest to rescue
your beloved Broomhilda.

712
00:50:37,535 --> 00:50:40,246
["I Got a Name" by Jim Croce playing]

713
00:50:43,541 --> 00:50:46,877
♪ <i>Like the pine trees</i>
<i>Lining the winding road ♪</i>

714
00:50:47,878 --> 00:50:52,341
♪ <i>I've got a name</i>
<i>I've got a name ♪</i>

715
00:50:52,925 --> 00:50:54,802
[indistinct chatter]

716
00:50:54,885 --> 00:50:58,055
♪ <i>Like the singin' bird</i>
<i>And the croakin' toad ♪</i>

717
00:50:58,931 --> 00:51:03,686
♪ <i>I've got a name</i>
<i>I've got a name ♪</i>

718
00:51:05,938 --> 00:51:09,483
♪ <i>And I carry it with me</i>
<i>Like my daddy did ♪</i>

719
00:51:10,150 --> 00:51:15,030
♪ <i>But I'm livin' the dream</i>
<i>That he kept hid ♪</i>

720
00:51:16,907 --> 00:51:19,034
<i>♪ Movin' me down the highway ♪</i>

721
00:51:19,577 --> 00:51:21,620
<i>♪ Rollin' me down the highway ♪</i>

722
00:51:22,121 --> 00:51:25,666
♪ <i>Movin' ahead</i>
<i>So life won't pass me by ♪</i>

723
00:51:30,796 --> 00:51:34,049
♪ <i>Like the north wind</i>
<i>Whistlin' down the sky ♪</i>

724
00:51:35,092 --> 00:51:39,305
♪ <i>I've got a song</i>
<i>I've got a song ♪</i>

725
00:51:41,849 --> 00:51:45,060
♪ <i>Like the whip-poor-will</i>
<i>And the baby's cry ♪</i>

726
00:51:46,103 --> 00:51:50,441
♪ <i>I've got a song</i>
<i>I've got a song ♪</i>

727
00:51:52,985 --> 00:51:56,614
♪ <i>And I carry it with me</i>
<i>And I sing it loud ♪</i>

728
00:51:57,197 --> 00:52:01,785
♪ <i>If it gets me nowhere</i>
<i>I'll go there proud ♪</i>

729
00:52:03,829 --> 00:52:08,626
♪ <i>Movin' me down the highway</i>
<i>Rollin' me down the highway ♪</i>

730
00:52:09,168 --> 00:52:12,588
♪ <i>Movin' ahead</i>
<i>So life won't pass me by ♪</i>

731
00:52:39,704 --> 00:52:40,824
[man] You got her.

732
00:52:41,033 --> 00:52:42,159
[sighs]

733
00:52:47,665 --> 00:52:51,835
Ooh! What happened to Mr. "I Wanna
Shoot White Folks for Money"?

734
00:52:52,901 --> 00:52:53,921
His son's with him.

735
00:52:54,254 --> 00:52:57,091
Well, good. He'll have
a loved one with him.

736
00:52:57,549 --> 00:52:59,385
Maybe even share a last word.

737
00:53:01,845 --> 00:53:03,263
That's better than most of them get.

738
00:53:04,056 --> 00:53:05,724
Damn sight better than he deserves.

739
00:53:14,483 --> 00:53:15,484
Put down the rifle.

740
00:53:18,987 --> 00:53:20,239
Don't worry, I'm not mad at you.

741
00:53:21,490 --> 00:53:23,492
Let's take out Smitty Bacall's handbill.

742
00:53:27,746 --> 00:53:28,914
Now, read it aloud.

743
00:53:29,957 --> 00:53:31,500
Consider that today's lesson.

744
00:53:34,294 --> 00:53:36,422
"Wanted, dead or alive.

745
00:53:38,132 --> 00:53:40,968
Smitty Bacall and the Smitty Bacall G..."

746
00:53:41,969 --> 00:53:43,262
-Gang.
-"...Gang...

747
00:53:44,388 --> 00:53:47,891
for murder and stagecoach ro...

748
00:53:49,407 --> 00:53:50,519
robbery.

749
00:53:51,186 --> 00:53:53,772
-Seven, zero, zero, zero--"
-Seven thousand.

750
00:53:53,856 --> 00:53:55,023
-Seven?
-Thousand.

751
00:53:55,899 --> 00:53:59,570
"Seven thousand dollars
for Smitty Bacall,

752
00:54:00,028 --> 00:54:06,285
One thousand, five hundred dollars
for each of his gang..."

753
00:54:07,494 --> 00:54:09,705
-Mem...
-"...members.

754
00:54:10,789 --> 00:54:15,169
Known members of the Smitty Bacall Gang
are as follas."

755
00:54:15,377 --> 00:54:16,920
-Follows.
-"Follows.

756
00:54:17,755 --> 00:54:20,382
Dandy Michaels, Gerald Nash, and..."

757
00:54:22,551 --> 00:54:23,594
Crazy Craig Koons.

758
00:54:25,304 --> 00:54:27,639
That is who Smitty Bacall is.

759
00:54:28,223 --> 00:54:30,809
If Smitty Bacall wanted
to start a farm at 22,

760
00:54:30,893 --> 00:54:32,311
they would never have printed that.

761
00:54:33,437 --> 00:54:36,690
But Smitty Bacall wanted
to rob stagecoaches,

762
00:54:37,232 --> 00:54:39,318
and he didn't mind
killing people to do it.

763
00:54:40,527 --> 00:54:43,238
Do you want to save your wife
by doing what I do?

764
00:54:44,823 --> 00:54:45,908
This is what I do.

765
00:54:46,450 --> 00:54:49,745
I kill people and sell
their corpses for cash.

766
00:54:50,913 --> 00:54:53,874
This corpse is worth 7,000 dollars.

767
00:54:54,666 --> 00:54:56,502
Now, quit your pussyfooting and shoot him.

768
00:55:01,882 --> 00:55:03,258
[horse neighs]

769
00:55:05,177 --> 00:55:06,191
[boy chuckles]

770
00:55:07,010 --> 00:55:08,013
[boy] Pa?

771
00:55:08,378 --> 00:55:09,431
Pa!

772
00:55:18,565 --> 00:55:22,236
Here. You need to keep
this Smitty Bacall handbill.

773
00:55:22,528 --> 00:55:24,238
-Why?
-It's good luck.

774
00:55:24,988 --> 00:55:27,115
You always keep the handbill
of your first bounty.

775
00:56:15,455 --> 00:56:16,832
That's accurate.

776
00:57:25,275 --> 00:57:27,903
[Gus] Doctor, Django,
how the hell are you?

777
00:57:29,404 --> 00:57:30,989
Who the hell have you got there?

778
00:57:31,615 --> 00:57:33,450
[Schultz] The Wilson-Lowe Gang.

779
00:57:34,117 --> 00:57:36,745
Who the hell is the Wilson-Lowe Gang?

780
00:57:37,788 --> 00:57:42,125
Bad Chuck Wilson and meaner Bobby Lowe
and three of their acolytes.

781
00:57:42,459 --> 00:57:46,046
Huh. Well, just leave them out here.
They ain't going nowhere.

782
00:57:46,296 --> 00:57:48,215
Why don't you come in
out of the snowy snow

783
00:57:48,298 --> 00:57:50,008
and get yourselves some coffee?

784
00:57:50,592 --> 00:57:53,178
We had a birthday, yesterday.
Got some cake.

785
00:57:53,762 --> 00:57:54,876
Pretty good.

786
00:58:17,077 --> 00:58:18,954
[man 1] Move along! Can't hide!

787
00:58:28,171 --> 00:58:31,216
[man 2] Keep moving. Get on up to that
auction block.

788
00:58:33,093 --> 00:58:35,429
Don't let that mud
slow you down. Keep going.

789
00:58:38,849 --> 00:58:39,850
[man 3] Come on.

790
00:58:51,945 --> 00:58:52,988
[man 4] Keep going.

791
00:58:55,907 --> 00:58:58,994
[Schultz] "Broomhilda Von Shaft. Age 27.

792
00:58:59,578 --> 00:59:01,079
'R' on right cheek.

793
00:59:03,040 --> 00:59:04,916
Calvin Candie."

794
00:59:05,292 --> 00:59:09,546
He owns the fourth biggest cotton
plantation in Mississippi. Candyland.

795
00:59:09,963 --> 00:59:11,002
Candyland?

796
00:59:11,465 --> 00:59:14,384
-Oh, you've heard of it!
-Ain't no slave ever heard of Candyland.

797
00:59:14,885 --> 00:59:17,054
Well, apparently,
that's where your wife is...

798
00:59:17,846 --> 00:59:20,599
and that's the repellant gentleman
who owns her.

799
00:59:20,724 --> 00:59:23,143
Let's just hope she works in the house,
not the field.

800
00:59:23,351 --> 00:59:24,686
Oh, no. She ain't no field nigger.

801
00:59:25,729 --> 00:59:27,105
She... She pretty.

802
00:59:28,356 --> 00:59:29,691
And she talk good, too.

803
00:59:31,568 --> 00:59:33,487
But when they tore her back up,
and then they...

804
00:59:34,821 --> 00:59:36,531
burned that runaway "R" on her cheek...

805
00:59:38,200 --> 00:59:39,409
they goddamned her.

806
00:59:39,993 --> 00:59:42,954
[screams]

807
00:59:43,955 --> 00:59:47,125
She ain't no field nigger, but she ain't
good enough for the house no more, either.

808
00:59:47,834 --> 00:59:51,129
-They'll try to make her a comfort girl.
-What's a comfort...? Oh.

809
00:59:52,130 --> 00:59:53,465
Not while I got freedom.

810
00:59:55,092 --> 00:59:56,384
Not while I got my gun.

811
00:59:59,721 --> 01:00:01,264
So, do we offer to buy her?

812
01:00:04,309 --> 01:00:05,310
So...

813
01:00:07,270 --> 01:00:08,355
say...

814
01:00:11,066 --> 01:00:13,527
a man wants to buy a horse.

815
01:00:14,236 --> 01:00:15,737
Needs to buy a horse.

816
01:00:17,572 --> 01:00:21,243
He walks up to the farmer's farm,
knocks on the door and asks the farmer

817
01:00:21,326 --> 01:00:24,121
to buy his horse. And you know
what the farmer says?

818
01:00:24,371 --> 01:00:26,206
The farmer says, "No."

819
01:00:28,125 --> 01:00:32,254
Well, I say, fuck that farmer.
And I'm stealing that horse.

820
01:00:33,130 --> 01:00:35,632
Fair enough.
But now, you're a horse thief,

821
01:00:35,715 --> 01:00:38,760
and they hang horse thieves.
Not to mention, the horse goes back

822
01:00:38,844 --> 01:00:41,513
to its original owner,
because the horse is still his property.

823
01:00:41,763 --> 01:00:45,308
We need her and we need a bill of sale.

824
01:00:45,475 --> 01:00:47,769
If we ain't gonna try to buy her,
how we gonna get her?

825
01:00:49,187 --> 01:00:52,691
May I offer an alternative plan of action?

826
01:00:52,980 --> 01:00:54,025
Go ahead.

827
01:00:54,693 --> 01:00:55,757
So...

828
01:00:56,361 --> 01:01:00,782
The man walks up to the farmer's farm,
he knocks on the farmer's door...

829
01:01:01,616 --> 01:01:06,538
and asks not to buy the horse,
but the farm.

830
01:01:06,663 --> 01:01:10,250
-Mm-hmm.
-And makes an offer so ridiculous,

831
01:01:10,417 --> 01:01:12,919
the farmer is forced to say, "Yes."

832
01:01:13,837 --> 01:01:16,882
-We gonna offer to buy Candyland?
-No, it's far too big.

833
01:01:16,965 --> 01:01:19,759
But apparently, this farmer
ain't all about the farm.

834
01:01:21,595 --> 01:01:23,597
How much do you know
about Mandingo fighting?

835
01:01:23,847 --> 01:01:24,861
What?

836
01:01:25,048 --> 01:01:29,642
Can you convincingly masquerade as someone
who is an expert on Mandingo fighting?

837
01:01:29,792 --> 01:01:30,812
Why?

838
01:01:31,146 --> 01:01:34,900
[Schultz] <i>Because my character is that</i>
<i>of a big money buyer from Dusseldorf</i>

839
01:01:34,983 --> 01:01:38,278
<i>here in Greenville to buy my way</i>
<i>into the Mandingo fight game.</i>

840
01:01:38,403 --> 01:01:42,324
<i>And your character is a Mandingo expert</i>
<i>I hired to help me do it.</i>

841
01:01:42,407 --> 01:01:44,034
[Django] <i>They call that "One-Eyed Charly."</i>

842
01:01:47,537 --> 01:01:48,705
<i>Bonjour!</i>

843
01:01:49,080 --> 01:01:52,209
<i>Bonsoir, mon petite femme noire!</i>

844
01:01:52,292 --> 01:01:54,544
We're here to see Mr. Calvin Candie.

845
01:01:55,128 --> 01:01:56,421
<i>Entrer.</i>

846
01:01:59,216 --> 01:02:00,217
[Schultz] Thank you.

847
01:02:01,593 --> 01:02:03,511
You want me to play a black slaver?

848
01:02:04,596 --> 01:02:06,473
Ain't nothing lower than a black slaver.

849
01:02:07,557 --> 01:02:10,435
A black slaver is lower
than the head house nigger.

850
01:02:11,436 --> 01:02:13,104
And buddy, that's pretty fucking low.

851
01:02:14,856 --> 01:02:16,816
Then play him that way.

852
01:02:16,900 --> 01:02:20,779
Give me your black slaver.

853
01:02:21,071 --> 01:02:23,365
[all]
<i>♪ His heart was all a-flutter ♪</i>

854
01:02:23,615 --> 01:02:27,035
<i>♪ Along came the 2:19 ♪</i>
<i>Toot, toot ♪</i>

855
01:02:27,244 --> 01:02:32,499
<i>♪ Peanut butter fare thee well</i>
<i>Fare thee well, fare thee well ♪</i>

856
01:02:32,582 --> 01:02:33,833
Dr. Schultz!

857
01:02:34,334 --> 01:02:37,212
-Good to see you again.
-Mr. Moguy!

858
01:02:37,545 --> 01:02:41,383
Thank you for your assistance in creating
the opportunity for this appointment.

859
01:02:41,466 --> 01:02:43,093
[Leo] Nonsense, it's my job.

860
01:02:43,635 --> 01:02:46,513
So, this is the One-Eyed Charly
I've heard so much about!

861
01:02:46,596 --> 01:02:48,848
Yes, this is Django Freeman.

862
01:02:49,307 --> 01:02:52,060
Django, this is Mr. Candie's lawyer,
Leonide Moguy.

863
01:02:52,143 --> 01:02:53,603
Just call me Leo.

864
01:02:53,895 --> 01:02:57,148
Calvin's in the Julius Caesar room.
You all wanna follow me?

865
01:02:57,649 --> 01:03:00,068
[Schultz] How long have you been
associated with Mr. Candie?

866
01:03:00,151 --> 01:03:02,654
[Leo] Oh, Calvin's father and I
were about 11

867
01:03:02,737 --> 01:03:04,364
when we went to boarding school together.

868
01:03:04,781 --> 01:03:07,659
Calvin's father's father
put me through law school.

869
01:03:07,742 --> 01:03:10,829
One could almost say I was raised
to be Calvin's lawyer.

870
01:03:10,912 --> 01:03:12,664
One could almost say youse a nigger.

871
01:03:13,623 --> 01:03:14,708
What did you say?

872
01:03:15,292 --> 01:03:17,836
-I said--
-Nothing, he's just being cheeky.

873
01:03:18,503 --> 01:03:22,924
Now, anything else about Mr. Candie
that I should know before I meet him?

874
01:03:23,008 --> 01:03:27,137
-Yes, he is a bit of a Francophile.
-[laughs] What civilized people aren't?

875
01:03:27,220 --> 01:03:29,597
{\an8}And he prefers Monsieur Candie
to Mr. Candie.

876
01:03:29,681 --> 01:03:31,808
{\an8}[speaks in French]

877
01:03:31,891 --> 01:03:34,728
{\an8}He doesn't speak French.
Don't speak French to him,

878
01:03:34,811 --> 01:03:35,895
it'll embarrass him.

879
01:03:37,564 --> 01:03:38,982
[men grunting]

880
01:03:39,065 --> 01:03:42,610
[Candie] Get back on top, now.
Turn around. There you go.

881
01:03:43,361 --> 01:03:44,529
There you go.

882
01:03:46,698 --> 01:03:49,034
Why do you want to get
in the Mandingo business?

883
01:03:51,703 --> 01:03:55,373
You don't intend to allow your second
to make the proper introductions?

884
01:03:56,374 --> 01:03:59,669
[Candie] Quit stalling, now.
Answer the question.

885
01:04:00,170 --> 01:04:01,880
[men continue grunting]

886
01:04:02,297 --> 01:04:03,590
The awful truth?

887
01:04:04,466 --> 01:04:07,719
I'm bored. This seems
like a good bit of fun.

888
01:04:13,391 --> 01:04:15,310
Well, come on over.

889
01:04:15,643 --> 01:04:17,979
We got us a fight going on
that's a good bit of fun.

890
01:04:20,065 --> 01:04:21,566
[Amerigo speaking in Italian]

891
01:04:22,025 --> 01:04:23,777
Won't you accompany me to the bar?

892
01:04:32,869 --> 01:04:35,538
You don't wear a hat in the house,
white man. Even I know that.

893
01:04:35,705 --> 01:04:38,750
[men grunting]

894
01:04:40,752 --> 01:04:42,087
[pool balls clacking]

895
01:04:44,547 --> 01:04:46,007
-Dr. Schultz.
-What a rare pleasure.

896
01:04:46,091 --> 01:04:49,302
-[Candie] Keep fighting, niggers!
-And, I might add, an honor.

897
01:04:49,719 --> 01:04:52,680
Honor to meet you. Please, have a seat.
The pleasure's all mine.

898
01:04:52,764 --> 01:04:55,600
Get free man Django, here,
whatever he wants.

899
01:04:56,393 --> 01:04:58,311
And I'll have sweet tea and bourbon.

900
01:05:16,162 --> 01:05:17,872
[both yelling]

901
01:05:18,289 --> 01:05:20,875
[Candie] Use your weight, boy,
use your weight! There you go.

902
01:05:21,584 --> 01:05:23,628
He's much bigger and stronger!

903
01:05:24,129 --> 01:05:25,338
Come on, now!

904
01:05:25,672 --> 01:05:28,299
Ah, he's not doing what I told him,
for God's sake!

905
01:05:28,758 --> 01:05:29,759
Bravo! Bravo, Luigi!

906
01:05:29,843 --> 01:05:32,178
[speaking in Italian]

907
01:05:32,429 --> 01:05:34,931
[Candie] Come on, now, boy!
It's a fight to the death!

908
01:05:36,558 --> 01:05:38,309
You either hit him or are you ain't?

909
01:05:38,560 --> 01:05:42,772
[men grunting and roaring]

910
01:05:42,856 --> 01:05:45,567
[speaking in Italian]

911
01:05:46,526 --> 01:05:48,611
Big Fred, come on!

912
01:05:49,487 --> 01:05:51,322
[Candie] Turn him around! Now, come...

913
01:05:54,826 --> 01:05:56,494
Use your strength, boy!

914
01:05:57,203 --> 01:05:58,997
Come on, now! Use your strength!

915
01:06:01,291 --> 01:06:02,417
There you go.

916
01:06:04,419 --> 01:06:05,587
There you go!

917
01:06:05,962 --> 01:06:06,963
Look at that.

918
01:06:07,922 --> 01:06:10,175
See, I told you to put
some more power in there.

919
01:06:11,176 --> 01:06:12,677
Do what I told you, boy.

920
01:06:13,428 --> 01:06:14,762
There you go.

921
01:06:14,971 --> 01:06:16,014
No.

922
01:06:16,306 --> 01:06:19,017
[Candie] Do what I told you!
Blind him black, boy!

923
01:06:19,225 --> 01:06:20,518
Blind him black!

924
01:06:20,977 --> 01:06:22,729
[Luigi screams]

925
01:06:22,896 --> 01:06:24,230
Oh, no, Luigi.

926
01:06:24,439 --> 01:06:26,274
[Luigi screams]

927
01:06:26,566 --> 01:06:27,567
[Candie] Yeah!

928
01:06:28,693 --> 01:06:32,113
[whoops]

929
01:06:33,072 --> 01:06:34,157
[sighs]

930
01:06:34,449 --> 01:06:37,285
[panting]

931
01:06:39,537 --> 01:06:41,539
[Luigi screaming]

932
01:06:45,102 --> 01:06:46,169
Finish him.

933
01:06:46,628 --> 01:06:50,006
[Luigi continues screaming]

934
01:06:50,798 --> 01:06:52,050
Go on, boy, finish him.

935
01:06:53,885 --> 01:06:55,386
-[hammer thuds]
-[Luigi is silent]

936
01:06:56,721 --> 01:07:00,350
[Leo] That's why they call him Big Fred.
Worth every penny.

937
01:07:00,433 --> 01:07:02,143
Well, <i>arrivederci, </i>Luigi!

938
01:07:02,352 --> 01:07:07,190
Come on up, now, boy. Get yourself a rest.
You did a fine job. A real fine job.

939
01:07:08,191 --> 01:07:09,275
Mercedes.

940
01:07:23,206 --> 01:07:24,999
[music box playing distantly]

941
01:07:30,838 --> 01:07:31,879
Tequila.

942
01:07:35,176 --> 01:07:37,095
[indistinct chatter]

943
01:07:42,183 --> 01:07:43,268
What's your name?

944
01:07:46,020 --> 01:07:47,059
Django.

945
01:07:49,732 --> 01:07:50,942
Can you spell it?

946
01:07:53,486 --> 01:07:57,615
D-J-A-N-G-O.

947
01:07:59,284 --> 01:08:00,451
The D is silent.

948
01:08:01,202 --> 01:08:02,224
I know.

949
01:08:09,252 --> 01:08:10,545
[Amerigo speaking in Italian]

950
01:08:10,628 --> 01:08:13,965
[Candie] Mr. Moguy, I want you
to take care of my new boy, here.

951
01:08:14,132 --> 01:08:18,219
You find him a room with a soft bed,
then bring him up a pony to lick his pole.

952
01:08:18,761 --> 01:08:21,598
But you be ready to travel to Candyland
tomorrow morning, now, you hear?

953
01:08:21,681 --> 01:08:24,183
-Yes, sir, Monsieur Candie.
-Before you go... Roscoe,

954
01:08:24,350 --> 01:08:26,352
get Fred here a tall beer.

955
01:08:30,648 --> 01:08:33,359
You enjoy that, boy. You've earned it.

956
01:08:33,735 --> 01:08:34,744
Yes, sir.

957
01:08:44,370 --> 01:08:45,788
What's your name, boy?

958
01:08:46,164 --> 01:08:48,166
His name is Django Freeman.

959
01:08:48,374 --> 01:08:49,423
[Candie chuckles]

960
01:08:51,836 --> 01:08:53,129
Where'd you dig him up?

961
01:08:53,546 --> 01:08:56,716
A fortuitous turn of events
brought Django and myself together.

962
01:08:58,635 --> 01:09:00,094
I've heard tell about you.

963
01:09:01,346 --> 01:09:04,474
I heard you been telling everybody
them Mandingos ain't no damn good,

964
01:09:04,557 --> 01:09:07,602
ain't nothing nobody is selling
is worth buying. I'm curious.

965
01:09:08,353 --> 01:09:10,355
What makes you such a Mandingo expert?

966
01:09:12,899 --> 01:09:15,026
I'm curious what makes you so curious.

967
01:09:18,571 --> 01:09:20,448
-What did you say, boy?
-Calm down, Butch.

968
01:09:21,699 --> 01:09:22,909
No offense given.

969
01:09:23,660 --> 01:09:24,674
None taken.

970
01:09:24,994 --> 01:09:26,204
[Schultz] Monsieur Candie,

971
01:09:26,788 --> 01:09:30,583
I'd appreciate if you could
direct your line of inquiry toward me.

972
01:09:30,750 --> 01:09:31,798
One...

973
01:09:32,794 --> 01:09:35,963
you do not have anything to drink.
Can I get you a tasty refreshment?

974
01:09:36,047 --> 01:09:38,841
-Yes. I'll have a beer.
-Wonder-bar!

975
01:09:39,092 --> 01:09:43,179
Roscoe, a beer for the man with the beard,
and I will have a Polynesian Pearl Diver.

976
01:09:43,262 --> 01:09:44,555
Do not spare the rum.

977
01:09:45,181 --> 01:09:46,195
Doc...

978
01:09:47,433 --> 01:09:50,978
I am a seasoned slaver.
You are... Well, you are a neophyte.

979
01:09:51,062 --> 01:09:55,566
I'm simply trying to ascertain if this
cowboy, here, is taking advantage of you.

980
01:09:57,443 --> 01:10:00,363
With all due respect, Monsieur Candie...

981
01:10:01,406 --> 01:10:03,116
I didn't seek you out for your advice.

982
01:10:03,491 --> 01:10:05,660
I sought you out to purchase
a fighting nigger

983
01:10:05,743 --> 01:10:07,704
at above top-dollar market price.

984
01:10:08,413 --> 01:10:11,165
I was under the impression,
when you granted me an audience,

985
01:10:11,249 --> 01:10:13,126
it would be to discuss business.

986
01:10:16,421 --> 01:10:18,131
Well, we weren't talking business yet.

987
01:10:18,923 --> 01:10:21,050
We were discussing my curiosity.

988
01:10:23,383 --> 01:10:24,429
Thank you.

989
01:10:24,512 --> 01:10:27,098
[Candie] Roscoe, Coco,
go outside and play.

990
01:10:29,350 --> 01:10:32,019
Sheba, you stay right there.

991
01:10:33,020 --> 01:10:34,522
I know you didn't mean me.

992
01:10:36,357 --> 01:10:37,358
<i>Prost!</i>

993
01:10:37,984 --> 01:10:39,002
German.

994
01:10:39,736 --> 01:10:41,070
Now, according to Moguy,

995
01:10:41,654 --> 01:10:45,533
if I do business with you,
I'm doing business with both y'all.

996
01:10:46,033 --> 01:10:48,327
He does the eyeballing,
you the billfold? Is that it?

997
01:10:48,703 --> 01:10:52,331
[chuckling] Well, you don't make it sound
too flattering, but more or less, yeah.

998
01:10:52,623 --> 01:10:53,655
Hmm.

999
01:10:54,834 --> 01:10:55,850
So...

1000
01:10:56,502 --> 01:11:00,339
Bright Boy, Moguy tells me
you looked over my African flesh

1001
01:11:00,423 --> 01:11:02,091
and you was none too impressed, huh?

1002
01:11:02,633 --> 01:11:03,760
Not for top dollar.

1003
01:11:06,429 --> 01:11:08,139
Then we got nothing more to talk about.

1004
01:11:08,514 --> 01:11:10,808
You see, you wanna buy
a beat-ass nigger from me,

1005
01:11:10,892 --> 01:11:12,977
those are the beat-ass niggers
I wanna sell, so...

1006
01:11:13,186 --> 01:11:15,146
He don't wanna buy the niggers
you wanna sell.

1007
01:11:16,063 --> 01:11:18,941
He wants the nigger you don't wanna sell.

1008
01:11:19,484 --> 01:11:23,488
Well, I don't sell the niggers
I don't wanna sell.

1009
01:11:26,073 --> 01:11:29,410
Well, you won't sell your best.

1010
01:11:29,827 --> 01:11:31,746
You won't even sell your second best.

1011
01:11:32,413 --> 01:11:35,750
But your third best? You don't want
to sell him either,

1012
01:11:36,334 --> 01:11:39,879
but if I made you an offer so ridiculous
you'd be forced to consider it...

1013
01:11:40,797 --> 01:11:42,965
[laughing] ...who knows what could happen?

1014
01:11:45,510 --> 01:11:47,386
And what do you consider ridiculous?

1015
01:11:48,721 --> 01:11:52,475
For a truly talented specimen?
The right nigger?

1016
01:11:54,602 --> 01:11:56,103
How much would you say, Django?

1017
01:11:59,941 --> 01:12:01,275
Twelve thousand dollars.

1018
01:12:02,318 --> 01:12:03,528
[Candie slurps]

1019
01:12:06,364 --> 01:12:09,617
Well, gentlemen, you had my curiosity,

1020
01:12:10,326 --> 01:12:11,702
but now, you have my attention.

1021
01:12:26,050 --> 01:12:28,010
[Candie] Willie? Willie.

1022
01:12:28,469 --> 01:12:30,012
Hold up. Hold up.

1023
01:12:30,638 --> 01:12:32,974
-Ah.
-Good morning, gentlemen.

1024
01:12:33,057 --> 01:12:36,018
Good Dr. Schultz.
Beautiful morning, isn't it?

1025
01:12:36,602 --> 01:12:38,104
You couldn't have picked a better one.

1026
01:12:38,437 --> 01:12:41,357
Please, won't you take a ride with us
here in the victoria?

1027
01:12:41,566 --> 01:12:43,067
[Schultz] Oh, thank you very much.

1028
01:12:43,150 --> 01:12:45,069
[Candie] You can tie
your horse up back there.

1029
01:12:53,536 --> 01:12:54,577
Django?

1030
01:12:59,417 --> 01:13:03,129
Where I part company from many
of my phrenologist colleagues

1031
01:13:03,421 --> 01:13:05,965
is I believe there is
a level above bright...

1032
01:13:06,924 --> 01:13:12,054
above talented, above loyal,
that a nigger can aspire to.

1033
01:13:13,180 --> 01:13:17,143
Say, one nigger
that just pops up in 10,000.

1034
01:13:17,852 --> 01:13:19,103
The exceptional nigger.

1035
01:13:20,438 --> 01:13:22,148
Bright day, huh, Bright Boy?

1036
01:13:23,524 --> 01:13:24,609
The sun is up.

1037
01:13:25,860 --> 01:13:27,486
It's shining on all of us.

1038
01:13:32,575 --> 01:13:33,618
Have a seat, doc.

1039
01:13:34,744 --> 01:13:36,704
Thank you. Quite an honor.

1040
01:13:36,954 --> 01:13:38,706
The honor is all ours. Thank you.

1041
01:13:38,956 --> 01:13:40,917
-[Schultz] Thank you.
-[Candie] <i>But I do believe that,</i>

1042
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:42,168
<i>given time,</i>

1043
01:13:42,460 --> 01:13:45,046
exceptional niggers
like Bright Boy, here...

1044
01:13:46,297 --> 01:13:47,965
become, if not frequent...

1045
01:13:49,383 --> 01:13:50,551
more frequent.

1046
01:13:52,929 --> 01:13:53,964
Right, boy?

1047
01:13:55,097 --> 01:13:57,016
You are that one in 10,000.

1048
01:13:57,600 --> 01:14:00,436
The name of the game is keep up,
not catch up, nigger.

1049
01:14:01,062 --> 01:14:02,271
[men laughing]

1050
01:14:13,199 --> 01:14:14,659
-Whoa!
-[horse neighs]

1051
01:14:16,577 --> 01:14:19,163
-Touch your guns, you die.
-[Candie] Everybody calm down.

1052
01:14:19,872 --> 01:14:21,999
Now, I saw the whole thing. No harm done.

1053
01:14:22,083 --> 01:14:25,252
-Are you kidding me? This nigger just--
-I said, no harm done!

1054
01:14:25,461 --> 01:14:27,338
Now, take your hand off your pistol!

1055
01:14:28,923 --> 01:14:31,509
Butch, that means you, too.

1056
01:14:33,010 --> 01:14:35,221
Everybody stop antagonizing my guest.

1057
01:14:37,390 --> 01:14:39,725
Hoot, get back up on your horse.

1058
01:14:40,518 --> 01:14:42,019
[Hoot] He broke my collarbone.

1059
01:14:42,103 --> 01:14:44,689
For God's sake,
somebody please help Hoot, here,

1060
01:14:44,772 --> 01:14:46,524
back up on his goddamn horse.

1061
01:14:46,857 --> 01:14:49,652
-[Nick] Yes, sir, boss.
-Oh, you are one lucky nigger.

1062
01:14:51,028 --> 01:14:52,905
You better listen to your boss, white boy.

1063
01:14:52,989 --> 01:14:55,116
Oh, I'm gonna go walking
in the moonlight with you.

1064
01:14:55,574 --> 01:14:56,784
You wanna hold my hand?

1065
01:14:57,535 --> 01:14:59,704
[chuckles]

1066
01:15:00,913 --> 01:15:03,457
["100 Black Coffins" by Rick Ross playing]

1067
01:15:03,541 --> 01:15:06,043
[Candie] Willie, take us home.

1068
01:15:08,546 --> 01:15:10,047
[Jessie] Here we go. Start moving.

1069
01:15:16,929 --> 01:15:17,930
[Billy] Head them out.

1070
01:15:26,313 --> 01:15:30,192
♪ <i>I need a hundred black</i>
<i>Coffins for a hundred bad men ♪</i>

1071
01:15:30,276 --> 01:15:33,362
♪ <i>A hundred black graves</i>
<i>So I can lay they ass in ♪</i>

1072
01:15:33,446 --> 01:15:36,866
♪ <i>I need a hundred black preachers</i>
<i>With a black sermon to tell ♪</i>

1073
01:15:36,949 --> 01:15:39,952
<i>♪ From a hundred black Bibles</i>
<i>While we send them all to hell ♪</i>

1074
01:15:40,036 --> 01:15:42,246
♪ <i>I need a hundred black coffins ♪</i>

1075
01:15:42,538 --> 01:15:45,916
♪ <i>Black coffins</i>
<i>Black coffins ♪</i>

1076
01:15:46,834 --> 01:15:49,253
♪ <i>I need a hundred black coffins ♪</i>

1077
01:15:49,420 --> 01:15:52,423
♪ <i>Black coffins, oh, Lord ♪</i>

1078
01:15:52,673 --> 01:15:55,092
♪ <i>Black coffins</i>
<i>I need a hundred ♪</i>

1079
01:16:03,726 --> 01:16:05,394
You got a problem with your eyeball, boy?

1080
01:16:05,728 --> 01:16:08,314
-No, sir.
-You want a boot heel in it?

1081
01:16:09,571 --> 01:16:10,649
No, sir.

1082
01:16:10,816 --> 01:16:13,110
Then you keep
your goddamn eyeballs off me.

1083
01:16:14,153 --> 01:16:17,156
Flash that bad look at me again,
I'll give you a reason not to like me.

1084
01:16:17,323 --> 01:16:18,407
Now, move, nigger!

1085
01:16:20,951 --> 01:16:23,037
You niggers are gonna understand
something about me.

1086
01:16:23,162 --> 01:16:25,039
I'm worse than any
of these white men here.

1087
01:16:25,331 --> 01:16:28,459
You get the molasses out your ass,
you keep your goddamn eyeballs off me.

1088
01:16:28,959 --> 01:16:32,129
He is a rambunctious sort,
ain't he? [chuckles]

1089
01:16:32,213 --> 01:16:33,422
Indeed!

1090
01:16:36,092 --> 01:16:39,345
May we stop for a moment so I may
put a word in my man's ear?

1091
01:16:39,887 --> 01:16:43,349
I'm expecting to fall in love
once I see the specimens at Candyland,

1092
01:16:43,474 --> 01:16:46,644
so before that moment,
it would be good if I could have

1093
01:16:46,727 --> 01:16:50,815
a confidential strategy meeting
with my confidant.

1094
01:16:54,193 --> 01:16:55,903
You mind telling me
what the hell you doing?

1095
01:16:56,028 --> 01:16:57,863
I confirmed that Broomhilda's
at Candyland.

1096
01:17:02,201 --> 01:17:04,870
-You're sure it's her?
-He didn't call her by name,

1097
01:17:04,954 --> 01:17:07,248
but she's a young lady,
whip marks on her back

1098
01:17:07,331 --> 01:17:10,376
and speaks German.
Now, while it's not wise to assume,

1099
01:17:10,459 --> 01:17:13,963
in this instance, I think
it's pretty safe. Point being...

1100
01:17:14,839 --> 01:17:17,424
don't get so carried away
with your retribution.

1101
01:17:18,050 --> 01:17:19,718
You lose sight of why we're here.

1102
01:17:19,927 --> 01:17:23,931
-You think I lost sight of that?
-Yes, I do. Stop antagonizing Candie.

1103
01:17:24,640 --> 01:17:29,645
You're going to blow this whole charade,
or, more than likely, get us both killed.

1104
01:17:29,728 --> 01:17:34,567
And I, for one, don't intend to die
in Chickasaw County, Mississippi, U.S.A.

1105
01:17:34,900 --> 01:17:37,611
I'm not antagonizing him.
I'm intriguing him.

1106
01:17:38,154 --> 01:17:40,322
You're yelling abuse at these poor slaves.

1107
01:17:41,365 --> 01:17:42,575
I recall the man...

1108
01:17:43,701 --> 01:17:46,620
who had me kill another man
in front of his son,

1109
01:17:47,121 --> 01:17:48,330
and he didn't bat a eye.

1110
01:17:50,121 --> 01:17:51,167
You remember that?

1111
01:17:53,627 --> 01:17:54,795
Yeah, of course I remember.

1112
01:17:54,879 --> 01:17:57,840
What you said was that this is my world.

1113
01:17:59,508 --> 01:18:01,135
And in my world, you gotta get dirty.

1114
01:18:02,553 --> 01:18:05,014
So, that's what I'm doing.
I'm getting dirty.

1115
01:18:09,143 --> 01:18:12,146
Well, you're paraphrasing a tad, but...

1116
01:18:13,647 --> 01:18:15,024
that was the general gist.

1117
01:18:19,612 --> 01:18:20,779
See you at Candyland.

1118
01:18:28,662 --> 01:18:30,998
[Django] All right, niggers. Back at it.

1119
01:18:32,583 --> 01:18:34,168
That means you too, Moonlight.

1120
01:18:54,855 --> 01:18:56,774
[dogs barking]

1121
01:19:21,715 --> 01:19:22,841
[Candie] I'll be.

1122
01:19:23,300 --> 01:19:24,301
D'Artagnan!

1123
01:19:25,219 --> 01:19:28,180
Now, boy, why do a fool thing
like run off?

1124
01:19:28,472 --> 01:19:30,766
I can't fight no more, Monsieur Candie.

1125
01:19:30,849 --> 01:19:32,101
[Candie] Yes, you can.

1126
01:19:32,434 --> 01:19:34,812
You might not be able to win,
but your ass can fight.

1127
01:19:35,896 --> 01:19:38,399
Mr. Stonesipher, would you please
shut these goddamn dogs up?

1128
01:19:38,524 --> 01:19:39,817
I cannot hear myself think!

1129
01:19:39,900 --> 01:19:42,152
Quieten down, Marsha! Marsha, hush up!

1130
01:19:42,236 --> 01:19:44,280
-[Marsha barks]
-[Stonesipher] Marsha! Hush up!

1131
01:19:44,697 --> 01:19:47,825
Hey! Get these goddamn dogs
away from this nigger!

1132
01:19:48,409 --> 01:19:50,577
[dogs whimpering]

1133
01:19:57,251 --> 01:19:58,502
Well, now, boy...

1134
01:19:59,712 --> 01:20:01,797
-get on out that tree.
-[D'Artagnan] Yes, sir.

1135
01:20:02,965 --> 01:20:06,302
[dogs barking]

1136
01:20:25,070 --> 01:20:26,447
How long was he loose?

1137
01:20:27,573 --> 01:20:29,658
A night. Day.

1138
01:20:30,826 --> 01:20:31,994
Half the other night.

1139
01:20:33,579 --> 01:20:35,039
How far he get off the property?

1140
01:20:35,456 --> 01:20:36,915
About 20 miles off prop.

1141
01:20:37,458 --> 01:20:39,626
Pretty far, considering that limp he got.

1142
01:20:42,254 --> 01:20:45,341
Mr. Moguy, who was D'Artagnan
supposed to fight on Friday?

1143
01:20:45,549 --> 01:20:46,884
One of this new lot.

1144
01:20:48,552 --> 01:20:51,305
Way he looks now, a blind Indian
wouldn't bet a bead on him.

1145
01:20:51,472 --> 01:20:54,141
[D'Artagnan] Please, Monsieur Candie,
I ain't got it in me no more.

1146
01:20:54,224 --> 01:20:57,227
Now, now, now. Now, no begging.

1147
01:20:58,479 --> 01:21:00,314
No playing on my soft heart.

1148
01:21:04,276 --> 01:21:06,487
-You in trouble now, son.
-Yes, sir.

1149
01:21:09,615 --> 01:21:12,701
You know, I done paid 500 dollars for you.

1150
01:21:13,410 --> 01:21:15,621
When I pay 500 dollars,

1151
01:21:16,246 --> 01:21:18,332
I expect to get five fights
out of a nigger

1152
01:21:18,415 --> 01:21:20,626
-before he roll over and play dead.
-Sir...

1153
01:21:21,126 --> 01:21:23,921
You got to understand,
I'm running a business here.

1154
01:21:25,089 --> 01:21:28,008
-You fought three fights.
-But I won every one!

1155
01:21:28,092 --> 01:21:30,511
Yes, you did. Yes, you did.
But that last one,

1156
01:21:30,594 --> 01:21:32,679
you muddled the line
between winning and losing.

1157
01:21:36,392 --> 01:21:37,893
Still, the fact remains.

1158
01:21:38,644 --> 01:21:41,939
I pay 500 dollars,
I want five goddamn fights.

1159
01:21:42,773 --> 01:21:44,525
So, what about my 500 dollars, huh?

1160
01:21:46,944 --> 01:21:48,404
What about my 500 dollars?

1161
01:21:50,364 --> 01:21:51,615
You gonna reimburse me?

1162
01:21:58,038 --> 01:21:59,832
You even know what "reimburse" means?

1163
01:21:59,915 --> 01:22:02,376
[all laughing]

1164
01:22:08,590 --> 01:22:10,092
[Schultz] I'll reimburse you.

1165
01:22:14,263 --> 01:22:15,263
You will?

1166
01:22:16,354 --> 01:22:17,391
Yep.

1167
01:22:20,769 --> 01:22:22,896
You'll pay 500 dollars...

1168
01:22:23,689 --> 01:22:27,234
for practically a one-eyed old Joe
ain't fit to push a broom?

1169
01:22:27,484 --> 01:22:28,485
No, he won't.

1170
01:22:30,821 --> 01:22:32,573
He just tired of you
toying with him, is all.

1171
01:22:33,907 --> 01:22:35,159
Matter of fact, so am I.

1172
01:22:36,326 --> 01:22:38,203
But we ain't paying a penny
for that piccaninny.

1173
01:22:38,537 --> 01:22:40,372
Ain't got no use for him.
Ain't that right, doc?

1174
01:22:42,207 --> 01:22:43,250
You heard him.

1175
01:22:52,801 --> 01:22:56,638
You're gonna have to excuse
Mr. Stonesipher's slack-jawed gaze.

1176
01:22:57,556 --> 01:23:00,058
He ain't never seen a nigger like you
ever in his life.

1177
01:23:00,934 --> 01:23:02,561
Ain't that right, Mr. Stonesipher?

1178
01:23:05,230 --> 01:23:06,275
That's right.

1179
01:23:07,524 --> 01:23:08,692
[Candie] For that matter...

1180
01:23:10,224 --> 01:23:11,361
nor have I.

1181
01:23:17,826 --> 01:23:18,952
Now,

1182
01:23:20,078 --> 01:23:23,123
seeing as you won't pay a penny
for this piccaninny, here...

1183
01:23:25,959 --> 01:23:28,795
you won't mind me handling this nigger
any way I see fit?

1184
01:23:30,339 --> 01:23:31,507
He's your nigger.

1185
01:23:35,594 --> 01:23:37,346
Mr. Stonesipher?

1186
01:23:38,764 --> 01:23:41,725
Let Marsha and her bitches
send D'Artagnan to nigger heaven.

1187
01:23:42,392 --> 01:23:44,186
[Stonesipher] Marsha!

1188
01:23:44,645 --> 01:23:46,230
Marsha, get him!

1189
01:23:46,522 --> 01:23:49,024
[dogs barking]

1190
01:23:49,274 --> 01:23:50,484
Get him, get him!

1191
01:23:52,069 --> 01:23:54,404
[all whooping]

1192
01:24:01,370 --> 01:24:02,788
[D'Artagnan screaming]

1193
01:24:11,338 --> 01:24:13,257
[screaming continues]

1194
01:24:24,726 --> 01:24:26,979
Your boss looks a little green
around the gills

1195
01:24:27,062 --> 01:24:28,981
for a blood sport like nigger-fighting.

1196
01:24:29,147 --> 01:24:30,190
No.

1197
01:24:30,732 --> 01:24:33,777
He just ain't used to seeing a man
ripped apart by dogs, is all.

1198
01:24:34,570 --> 01:24:35,637
Mm.

1199
01:24:36,738 --> 01:24:37,781
You are used to it?

1200
